title: Non-negative Tensor Mixture Learning for Discrete Density Estimation

sections.text:
#### Abstract

We present an expectation-maximization (EM) based unified framework for nonnegative tensor decomposition that optimizes the Kullback-Leibler divergence. To avoid iterations in each M-step and learning rate tuning, we establish a general relationship between low-rank decompositions and many-body approximations. Using this connection, we exploit that the closed-form solution of the many-body approximation updates all parameters simultaneously in the M-step. Our framework offers not only a unified methodology for a variety of low-rank structures, including CP, Tucker, and Tensor Train decompositions, but also their mixtures. Notably, the weights of each low-rank tensor in the mixture can be learned from the data, which enables us to leverage the advantage of different low-rank structures without careful selection of the structure in advance. We empirically demonstrate that our framework overall provides superior generalization in terms of discrete density estimation and classification when compared to conventional tensor-based approaches.

## 1 Introduction

Tensors are versatile data structures used in a broad range of fields including signal processing [55], computer vision [46], and data mining [47]. It is an established fact that features can be extracted from tensor-formatted data by low-rank decomposition, which approximates the tensor by a linear combination of a few bases [10, 37]. There are numerous variations of low-rank structure used in the decomposed representation, such as CP [23, 5], Tucker [61], and Tensor Train (TT) [45], and the user needs to select one structure in advance before performing the decomposition.

A series of recent studies [21, 42] show that tensor low-rank decomposition is also useful for discrete density estimation, which is an interesting application that takes advantage of the discreteness of the tensor indices. Specifically, given observed discrete samples $\boldsymbol{x}^{(1)}, \ldots, \boldsymbol{x}^{(N)}$, the empirical distribution $p(\boldsymbol{x})$ can be regarded as a non-negative normalized tensor $\mathcal{T}$, called an empirical tensor, and its low-rank reconstruction $\mathcal{P}$ approximates the true distribution as seen in Figure 1. The obtained density can then be used for multiple purposes, such as predicting new data points, classification, inferring missing values, or performing outlier detection [54]; however, two challenges remain in these current works.

The first challenge is to develop a unified formulation of nonnegative tensor decomposition that works with various kinds of low-rank structures, optimizing the Kullback-Leibler (KL) divergence, which is a natural measure of similarity between probability distributions. In contrast to the well-

Consequently, some existing studies of tensor-based density estimation have been performed via optimization of the Frobenius norm [30, 29, 14, 42, 62]. In addition, due to the lack of a unified KL-divergence-based framework, users must either perform the decompositions with only low-rank structures that have already been developed in a piecemeal manner or differentiate the cost function for the target low-rank structure by themselves. A principled approach that allows users to try various low-rank structures more freely is, therefore, desirable.
The second challenge is scalability, as the size of the tensor - which corresponds to the sample space size of the discrete distribution - increases exponentially with the number of features $D$, namely when the degree of freedom of each feature is $I$, the associated joint distribution tensor has $I^{D}$ elements. However, the number of samples available for training $N$ - typically corresponds to the number of nonzero values of the empirical tensor - is often limited. Therefore, it is desirable to develop scalable tensor decomposition procedures that work with high-dimensional data facing a limited number of sampled observations.

To address these two challenges, we proposes a unified non-negative tensor factorization method based on the expectation-maximization (EM) algorithm [12]. The EM algorithm is an iterative framework for maximum likelihood estimation that repeatedly maximizes the lower bound of the log-likelihood function in two steps, the E-step and the M-step. The naive EM-based formulation for general non-negative tensor decomposition involves either alternating optimization to bound the log-likelihood (E-step) and maximizing each factor individually (M-step), or using gradient-based methods in each M-step. The former approach requires tailoring methods for each type of low-rank structure, while the latter is computationally expensive because of the additional iteration for the gradient method inside the EM iteration. To overcome this issue, we exploit that the optimization in each M-step coincides with a tensor many-body approximation [19] that decomposes tensors by a representation with reduced interactions among tensor modes. We derive the exact closedform solution for many-body approximation that appears in the M-step for the Tucker and TT decompositions, and thereby successfully remove the gradient method in the M-step for various kinds of low-rank decomposition by combining these two formulas.
Our framework inherits the properties of the EM algorithm [27], and therefore, it always converges regardless of the choice of the low-rank structure assumed in the model. Furthermore, the tensor to be approximated in the M-step is sparse as it is defined in terms of elementwise multiplications by the empirical tensor. As a result, the computational complexity of the proposed method is proportional to the number of samples $N$. Notably, as the EM algorithm is frequently used for maximum likelihood estimation of mixture models, the proposed method allows for density estimation with mixtures of low-rank tensors providing flexible modeling. The mixture model automatically finds appropriate weights for mixed low-rank structures, eliminating the need for the user to define a single low-rank structure in advance, which allows hybridization of the merits of each low-rank structure, i.e., the direct representation in CP and the latent interaction in TT.
Moreover, the flexibility allows us to mix a low-rank tensor with a constant tensor, which incorporates the noise of the data and stabilizes learning. While adding a small uniform constant to a tensor is often used as a heuristic to stabilize learning [11, 20], our method provides a principled approach to learning the constant from the data. We empirically show that such mixture of low-rank modeling provides better generalization in classification and density estimation tasks than pure low-rank tensor models. We summarize our contribution as follows:

- We reveal a relationship between tensor many-body approximation and low-rank decomposition.
- Using this relationship, we provide a unified EM-based framework for non-negative low-rank decompositions optimizing the KL-divergence with closed-form updates for all parameters in the M-step.
- Based on the proposed framework, we develop a mixture of low-rank tensor modeling that empirically demonstrates inferential robustness and improved generalization.
In the remainder of this section, we describe the problem settings, followed by the definition of many-body approximation, which forms the foundation of this study.
Problem setup We construct a normalized empirical tensor, or empirical distribution, from the given tabular data set with $D$ categorical features. The distribution is identical to a normalized $D$-th order tensor $\mathcal{T} \in \mathbb{R}_{\geq 0}^{I_{1} \times \cdots \times I_{D}}$ where $I_{d}$ is the degree of freedom (i.e., categories) of the $d$-th categorical feature. The number of non-zero values in the tensor is equivalent to the number of observed samples $N$ if there is no identical sample in the data. To estimate the discrete probability distribution underlying the data, we approximate the tensor $\mathcal{T}$ with a low-rank tensor considering the CP, Tucker, and TT formats, or their mixture as a convex linear combination of low-rank tensors. The setup for $D=3$ is shown in Figure 1.
Many-body approximation for tensors The many-body approximation decomposes the tensor (discrete distribution) by the interactions among the modes (random variables) described by the interaction diagram. We provide here an example of the diagram for a fourth-order tensor in Figure 2 where each node (circle) corresponds to a tensor mode and each edge through a black square, $\boldsymbol{\square}$, denotes the existence of interaction. For a given tensor $\mathcal{T}$, the approximation corresponding to the diagram can be written as $\mathcal{T}_{i j k l} \simeq \mathcal{P}_{i j k l}=\mathcal{A}_{i j k} B_{i j} C_{i l} D_{j l}$ where matrices $B, C$, and $D$ define two-body interactions whereas the tensor $\mathcal{A}$ defines a three-body interaction. The many-body approximation always provides a globally optimal solution $\mathcal{P}$ that minimizes the KL divergence

# 2 Related works 

The EM algorithm is widely used to train models with hidden variables [12]. We apply the EM algorithm to tensor decomposition by regarding tensor indices as visible variables and ranks as hidden variables. Several studies have shown that decomposing an empirical tensor constructed from observed samples can be used to estimate the underlying distribution behind the data [29, 21, 26, 62]. For density estimation, the KL divergence is a natural choice for the objective function of tensor decomposition, and the multiplicative updates methods (MU) are here often used to find the low-rank tensor by optimizing the KL divergence from an empirical tensor [31, 49]. The present EM-based method has not been established except for the CP decomposition [24, 65, 6]. Importantly, our work provides EM-based decomposition for various low-rank structures and their mixtures and enables the update of all parameters simultaneously, which differs from the MU methods that alternatingly update a specific set of parameters while keeping the other parameters fixed. Although a mixture model with the same low-rank structures is considered in [63], our approach incorporates a mixture of different low-rank structures, which is a more general framework. Recently, density estimation methods using second and third-order marginals have been developed [30, 26, 22]. However, these methods are so far limited to considering the CP decomposition-based model and typically require hyper-parameters for the gradient method, whereas the convergence of the algorithms has not been fully discussed. In this context, our approach directly applies to various low-rank structures with hyper-parameter-free optimization and guarantees monotonically decreasing error functions and convergence.
In probabilistic tensor decomposition, tensor elements are sampled from a distribution $p_{\theta}$ and the model parameter $\theta$ is optimized via the EM algorithm [32, 66, 51]. We note that our setting is different from these works as we do not assume any distribution behind each element of the tensor. Furthermore, the EM algorithm is often used for tensor completion, treating missing values as hidden variables [60, 39, 56]. This task assumes $\mathcal{T}_{\boldsymbol{i}}=\mathcal{P}_{\boldsymbol{i}}$ where $\mathcal{T}$ is the given tensor including missing values, $\mathcal{P}$ is the reconstructed low-rank tensor, and $\boldsymbol{i}$ is an index on observed elements of $\mathcal{T}$. Density estimation does not impose this constraint. It has also been reported that the EM algorithm can be applied to sum-product networks [13] by regarding sum-nodes as hidden variables [48]. # 3 Low-rank approximation and many-body approximation 

The naive EM-based formulation for non-negative low-rank approximation, which bounds the likelihood in the E-step and optimizes parameters in the M-step, typically relies on an iterative gradient method during the M-step. Importantly, we point out that the M-step can be regarded as a many-body approximation for a higher-order tensor, and the gradient method in the M-step is eliminated by the closed-form solution of the many-body approximation derived below.
In the following, we identify a normalized nonnegative tensor with a discrete distribution. Specifically, the tensor element $\mathcal{T}_{i_{1}, \ldots, i_{D}}$ is regarded as the value of the distribution $p\left(x_{1}=i_{1}, \ldots, x_{D}=i_{D}\right)$.

### 3.1 Many-body approximation with exact solution

As a preliminary step towards a unified EM tensor decomposition in Section 4, we here consider the following three kinds of many-body approximations for non-negative normalized tensors, namely a $(D+1)$-th order tensor $\mathcal{Q}^{\mathrm{CP}} \in \mathbb{R}_{\geq 0}^{I_{1} \times \cdots \times I_{D} \times R}$, a $2 D$-th order tensor $\mathcal{Q}^{\text {Tucker }} \in$ $\mathbb{R}_{\geq 0}^{I_{1} \times \cdots \times I_{D} \times R_{1} \times \cdots \times R_{D}}$, and a $(2 D-1)$-th order tensor $\mathcal{Q}^{\mathrm{TT}} \in \mathbb{R}_{\geq 0}^{I_{1} \times \cdots \times I_{D} \times R_{1} \times \cdots \times R_{D-1}}$. When their interactions are described as Figure 3(a), (b), and (c) respectively, they can be factorized as

$$
\mathcal{Q}_{i_{1} \ldots i_{D} r}^{\mathrm{CP}}=\prod_{d=1}^{D} A_{i_{d} r}^{(d)}, \quad \mathcal{Q}_{i_{1} \ldots i_{D} r_{1} \ldots r_{D}}^{\text {Tucker }}=\mathcal{G}_{r_{1} \ldots r_{D}} \prod_{d=1}^{D} A_{i_{d} r_{d}}^{(d)}, \quad \mathcal{Q}_{i_{1} \ldots i_{D} r_{1} \ldots r_{D-1}}^{\mathrm{TT}}=\prod_{d=1}^{D} \mathcal{G}_{r_{d-1} i_{d} r_{d}}^{(d)}
$$

where $i_{d} \in\left[I_{d}\right]$ and $r_{d} \in\left[R_{d}\right]$ for $d=1, \ldots, D$. For simplicity, we suppose $r_{0}=r_{D}=1$ for $\mathcal{Q}^{\mathrm{TT}}$. Let tensor indices $i_{1}, \ldots, i_{D}$ and $r_{1}, \ldots, r_{V}$ be $\boldsymbol{i}$ and $\boldsymbol{r}$, respectively, where the integer $V$ is 1 for $\mathcal{Q}^{\mathrm{CP}}, D$ for $\mathcal{Q}^{\text {Tucker }}$, and $D-1$ for $\mathcal{Q}^{\mathrm{TT}}$. We denote the domains of $\boldsymbol{i}$ and $\boldsymbol{r}$ by $\Omega_{I}$ and $\Omega_{R}$, respectively, i.e., $\boldsymbol{i} \in \Omega_{I}=\left[I_{1}\right] \times \cdots \times\left[I_{D}\right]$ and $\boldsymbol{r} \in \Omega_{R}=\left[R_{1}\right] \times \cdots \times\left[R_{V}\right]$. The symbol $\Omega$ with upper indices refers to the index set for all indices other than the upper indices, e.g.,

$$
\begin{aligned}
\Omega_{I}^{\backslash d} & =\left[I_{1}\right] \times \cdots \times\left[I_{d-1}\right] \times\left[I_{d+1}\right] \times \cdots \times\left[I_{D}\right] \\
\Omega_{R}^{\backslash d, d-1} & =\left[R_{1}\right] \times \cdots \times\left[R_{d-2}\right] \times\left[R_{d+1}\right] \times \cdots \times\left[R_{V}\right]
\end{aligned}
$$

Many-body approximation parameterizes tensors as discrete distributions, where the random variables correspond to the tensor modes, and the sample space corresponds to the index set of a tensor. Maximum likelihood estimation finds the globally optimal tensor that minimizes the KL divergence from a given tensor $\mathcal{M}$ onto the model space $\boldsymbol{B}$, which is the set of tensors with specific interactions.

Thus, for a given tensor $\mathcal{M}$, the many-body approximation based on the above three interactions maximizes

$$
L_{\mathrm{MBA}}\left(\mathcal{M} ; \mathcal{Q}^{k}\right)=\sum_{\boldsymbol{i} \in \Omega_{I}} \sum_{\boldsymbol{r} \in \Omega_{R}} \mathcal{M}_{\boldsymbol{i} \boldsymbol{r}} \log \mathcal{Q}_{\boldsymbol{i} \boldsymbol{r}}^{k}
$$

for $k \in\{\mathrm{CP}$, Tucker, TT $\}$. This optimization is guaranteed to be a convex problem regardless of the choice of interaction. It has been shown in $[24,65]$ that the following matrices globally maximize $L_{\mathrm{MBA}}\left(\mathcal{M} ; \mathcal{Q}^{\mathrm{CP}}\right)$ :

$$
A_{i_{d} r}^{(d)}=\frac{\sum_{\boldsymbol{i} \in \Omega_{I}^{\prime d}} \mathcal{M}_{\boldsymbol{i} r}}{\mu^{1 / D}\left(\sum_{\boldsymbol{i} \in \Omega_{I}} \mathcal{M}_{\boldsymbol{i} r}\right)^{1-1 / D}}
$$

for $\mu=\sum_{\boldsymbol{i} \in \Omega_{I}} \sum_{r \in \Omega_{R}} \mathcal{M}_{\boldsymbol{i} r}$, which is consistent with a mean-field approximation [17, 18]. As a generalization of the above result, we presently provide the optimal solution of the many-body approximation of $\mathcal{Q}^{\text {Tucker }}$ and $\mathcal{Q}^{\mathrm{TT}}$ in closed-form. The following tensors globally maximizes $L_{\mathrm{MBA}}\left(\mathcal{M} ; \mathcal{Q}^{\text {Tucker }}\right)$ :

$$
\mathcal{G}_{\boldsymbol{r}}=\frac{\sum_{\boldsymbol{i} \in \Omega_{I}} \mathcal{M}_{\boldsymbol{i} \boldsymbol{r}}}{\sum_{\boldsymbol{i} \in \Omega_{I}} \sum_{\boldsymbol{r} \in \Omega_{R}} \mathcal{M}_{\boldsymbol{i} \boldsymbol{r}}}, \quad A_{i_{d} r_{d}}^{(d)}=\frac{\sum_{\boldsymbol{i} \in \Omega_{I}^{\prime d}} \sum_{\boldsymbol{r} \in \Omega_{R}^{\prime d}} \mathcal{M}_{\boldsymbol{i} \boldsymbol{r}}}{\sum_{\boldsymbol{i} \in \Omega_{I}} \sum_{\boldsymbol{r} \in \Omega_{R}^{\prime d}} \mathcal{M}_{\boldsymbol{i} \boldsymbol{r}}}
$$

and the following tensors globally maximizes $L_{\mathrm{MBA}}\left(\mathcal{M} ; \mathcal{Q}^{\mathrm{TT}}\right)$ :

$$
\mathcal{G}_{r_{d-1} i_{d} r_{d}}^{(d)}=\frac{\sum_{\boldsymbol{i} \in \Omega_{I}^{\prime d}} \sum_{\boldsymbol{r} \in \Omega_{R}^{\prime d, d-1}} \mathcal{M}_{\boldsymbol{i} \boldsymbol{r}}}{\sum_{\boldsymbol{i} \in \Omega_{I}} \sum_{\boldsymbol{r} \in \Omega_{R}^{\prime d}} \mathcal{M}_{\boldsymbol{i} \boldsymbol{r}}}
$$

where we assume $r_{0}=r_{D}=1$. We formally derive the above closed-form solutions in Theorems 2 and 3 in the supplementary material. Notably, we can obtain exact solutions also for more complicated many-body approximations by combining these solutions, which we discuss in Section 4.3.

# 4 Density estimation via tensor learning 

Based on the exact solutions of the many-body approximation derived in Section 3, we develop a novel framework EM non-negative tensor learning for discrete density estimation. Our framework has two advantages: (1) it achieves linear computational complexity relative to the number of nonzero elements in the input tensor, as described in Section 4.2; and (2) it offers the flexibility to incorporate various low-rank structures, such as CP, Tucker, TT, their mixtures, and adaptive noise terms, while preserving the convexity of E-step and M-step, as detailed in Sections 4.3. Neither of these advantages has been explored in MU methods [31]. In the following, tensor indices for mixtures are expressed as superscripts without parentheses.

### 4.1 EM-method for mixture of low-rank tensors

We maximize the negative cross-entropy from a given $D$-th order tensor $\mathcal{T}$ to a mixture of $K$ low-rank tensors $\mathcal{P}^{1}, \ldots, \mathcal{P}^{K}$,

$$
L(\hat{\mathcal{Q}})=\sum_{i \in \Omega_{I}} \mathcal{T}_{i} \log \sum_{k=1}^{K} \eta^{k} \mathcal{P}_{i}^{k}, \quad \mathcal{P}_{i}^{k}=\sum_{r \in \Omega_{R^{k}}} \mathcal{Q}_{i r}^{k}
$$

where the mixture ratio satisfies $\sum_{k} \eta^{k}=1$ and $\eta^{k} \geq 0$ for all $k \in[K]$ and setting $K=1$ provides a conventional low-rank tensor decomposition. Each low-rank tensor $\mathcal{P}^{k}$ is normalized, i.e., $\sum_{i} \mathcal{P}_{i}^{k}=1$. We let the model $\mathcal{P}$ be the convex linear combination of low-rank tensors, that is, $\mathcal{P}=\sum_{k=1}^{K} \eta^{k} \mathcal{P}^{k}$. We denote the number of hidden variables in the tensor $\mathcal{Q}^{k}$ by $V^{k}$, and $r \in \Omega_{R^{k}}=\left[R_{1}^{k}\right] \times \cdots \times\left[R_{V^{k}}^{k}\right]$. For simplicity, we introduce $\hat{\mathcal{Q}}_{i r}^{k}=\eta^{k} \mathcal{Q}_{i r}^{k}$, and refer to the tensors $\left(\hat{\mathcal{Q}}^{1}, \ldots, \hat{\mathcal{Q}}^{K}\right)$ as $\hat{\mathcal{Q}}$. We apply Jensen's inequality [28] to the objective function $L(\hat{\mathcal{Q}})$ and move the summation over hidden variables $r$ outside the logarithm function thereby obtaining the lower bound as

$$
L(\hat{\mathcal{Q}}) \geq \bar{L}(\hat{\mathcal{Q}}, \Phi)=\sum_{i \in \Omega_{I}} \sum_{k=1}^{K} \sum_{r \in \Omega_{R^{k}}} \mathcal{T}_{i} \Phi_{i r}^{k} \log \frac{\hat{\mathcal{Q}}_{i r}^{k}}{\Phi_{i r}^{k}}
$$

for any $K$ tensors $\Phi=\left(\Phi^{1}, \ldots, \Phi^{K}\right)$ and $\left(D+V^{k}\right)$-th order tensor $\Phi^{k}$ satisfying $\sum_{k} \sum_{r \in \Omega_{R^{k}}} \Phi_{i r}^{k}=1$. The derivation of the inequality (8) is described in Proposition 1 in the supplementary material. The above lower bound can be decoupled into independent multiple manybody approximations for tensors $\mathcal{M}^{1}, \ldots, \mathcal{M}^{K}$ where each tensor $\mathcal{M}^{k}$ is defined as $\mathcal{M}_{i r}^{k}=\mathcal{T}_{i} \Phi_{i r}^{k}$, and an optimization problem for the mixture ratio $\eta=\left(\eta^{1}, \ldots, \eta^{K}\right)$. More specifically, we decouple the lower bound as follows:

$$
\bar{L}(\hat{\mathcal{Q}}, \Phi)=\sum_{k=1}^{K} L_{\mathrm{MBA}}\left(\mathcal{M}^{k} ; \mathcal{Q}^{k}\right)+J(\eta), \quad J(\eta)=\sum_{i \in \Omega_{I}} \sum_{k=1}^{K} \sum_{r \in \Omega_{R^{k}}} \mathcal{T}_{i} \Phi_{i r}^{k} \log \eta^{k}
$$

where the objective function of many-body approximation $L_{\mathrm{MBA}}$ is introduced in Equation (2). The EM algorithm iteratively optimizes the lower bound for tensors $\Phi$ in the E-step and tensors $\hat{\mathcal{Q}}$ in the M-step until convergence. While we show that the E-step and M-step are both guaranteed to be

globally optimal, forming convex sub-problems, the entire procedure remains non-convex and suffers from the initial value dependency.
E-step We maximize the lower bound $\bar{L}(\tilde{\mathcal{Q}}, \Phi)$ for tensors $\Phi=\left(\Phi^{1}, \ldots, \Phi^{K}\right)$, that is, $\Phi=$ $\arg \max _{\Phi \in \mathcal{D}} \bar{L}(\tilde{\mathcal{Q}}, \Phi)$, where the set $\mathcal{D}$ is a tuple of $K$ tensors such that each tensor is normalized by hidden variables, i.e., $\mathcal{D}=\left\{\left(\Phi^{1}, \ldots, \Phi^{K}\right) \mid \sum_{k} \sum_{\boldsymbol{r} \in \Omega_{R^{k}}} \Phi_{\boldsymbol{i r}}^{k}=1\right\}$. The optimal solution $\Phi^{k}$ is

$$
\Phi_{\boldsymbol{i r}}^{k}=\frac{\tilde{\mathcal{Q}}_{\boldsymbol{i r}}^{k}}{\sum_{k=1}^{K} \sum_{\boldsymbol{r} \in \Omega_{R^{k}}} \tilde{\mathcal{Q}}_{\boldsymbol{i r}}^{k}}
$$

as shown in Proposition 2 in the supplementary material.
M-step We maximize the lower bound $\bar{L}(\tilde{\mathcal{Q}}, \Phi)$ for tensors $\mathcal{Q}=\left(\mathcal{Q}^{1}, \ldots, \mathcal{Q}^{K}\right)$ and non-negative weights $\eta$. Since the lower bound can be decoupled as shown in Equation (9), the required optimizations in the M-step are as follows:

$$
\mathcal{Q}^{k}=\underset{\mathcal{Q}^{k} \in \boldsymbol{B}^{k}}{\arg \max } L_{\mathrm{MBA}}\left(\mathcal{M}^{k} ; \mathcal{Q}^{k}\right), \quad \eta=\underset{0 \leq \eta^{k} \leq 1, \sum_{k} \eta^{k}=1}{\arg \max } J(\eta)
$$

where the model space $\boldsymbol{B}^{k}$ is the set of low-body tensors corresponding to the $k$-th low-rank tensor $\mathcal{P}^{k}$. The naive implementation of the M-step requires the Natural gradient method to solve the many-body approximation for $\mathcal{M}^{k}$, which takes cubic computational complexity for the number of parameters in the low-body tensor $\mathcal{Q}^{k}$ [2]. Thus, repeating the M-step is computationally expensive. However, we introduced the closed-form solution of the many-body approximation in Section 3.1, which eliminates the iterative gradient method in the M-step for the Tucker and TT decompositions. We discuss more complicated low-rank structures in Section 4.3.
We also provide the optimal update rule for the mixture ratio $\eta$ in closed form. By the condition $\partial J(\eta) / \partial \eta^{k}=0$ and $\sum_{k} \eta^{k}=1$, the optimal $\eta^{k}$ is simply given as follows:

$$
\eta^{k}=\frac{\sum_{i \in \Omega_{I}} \sum_{\boldsymbol{r} \in \Omega_{R^{k}}} \mathcal{M}_{\boldsymbol{i r}}^{k}}{\sum_{k=1}^{K} \sum_{i \in \Omega_{I}} \sum_{\boldsymbol{r} \in \Omega_{R^{k}}} \mathcal{M}_{\boldsymbol{i r}}^{k}}
$$

which is shown in Proposition 3 in the supplementary material. It is straightforward to check that the M-step is a convex optimization problem no matter what low-rank structure is assumed on $\mathcal{P}^{k}$ since we can decouple the lower bound into independent many-body approximations.

While the EM-based method for CP decomposition optimizing the KL divergence has already been developed in $[24,65]$, our proposed approach addresses more general low-rank decompositions and their mixtures. We provide the entire algorithm in Algorithm 1. Notably, the framework does not require a learning rate that needs to be carefully tuned when relying on gradient-based methods. Moreover, the proposed method updates all parameters simultaneously in closed form, which differs from the multiplicative update rule such as [31]. The extension to non-normalized non-negative tensors is described in Section C. 2 of the supplemental material.
Adaptive noise learning Our approach deals not only with typical low-rank structures and their mixtures but also with noise terms. For example, we here define model $\mathcal{P}$ as the mixture of a low-rank tensor $\mathcal{P}^{\text {low-rank }}$ and a normalized uniform tensor $\mathcal{P}^{\text {noise }}$ whose elements all are $1 / \mid \Omega_{I} \mid$ as $\mathcal{P}=\left(1-\eta^{\text {noise }}\right) \mathcal{P}^{\text {low-rank }}+\eta^{\text {noise }} \mathcal{P}^{\text {noise }}$, for $\left|\Omega_{I}\right|=I_{1} I_{2} \ldots I_{D}$. The learnable parameter $\eta^{\text {noise }}$ indicates the magnitude of global shift or background noise in the data. It is obvious from the above discussion that the convergence remains even in the presence of the noise term. We show in Section 5 that the noise term also stabilizes the learning.
Selection of mixture components As shown above, our framework supports the mixtures of lowrank tensors. This flexibility raises the question of how to determine the components of the mixture. One approach is to manually select the low-rank structures to leverage the strengths of different structures to improve generalization in density estimation. For instance, the CP decomposition offers an intuitive representation with fewer parameters; the TT decomposition captures latent pairwise interactions using more parameters; while the Tucker decomposition accounts for all combinations of latent interactions across the attributes, resulting in an exponential increase in the number of parameters. Alternatively, we can employ cross-validation to automatically select suitable structures. We also emphasize that it is not always possible to uniquely define the optimal mixture components

for a given dataset, as low-rank structures can overlap - for example, a rank- $R$ CP decomposition can be expressed using a rank- $R$ TT decomposition.

Convergence analysis Regardless of the low-rank structure, the proposed algorithm is guaranteed to converge, and each iteration increases the objective function (7) monotonically, which we prove in Theorem 4 in the supplementary material while the general convergence theorem of the MU method is still an open problem, requiring proof of convergence for each minor change in the objective function, such as varying the low-rank structure or adding regularization terms. Furthermore, the limit point $\tilde{\mathcal{Q}}^{*}$ of the point sequence generated by the proposed algorithm is always included in the domain of the objective function $L$, and the Lagrange function with $L$ and the constraints for interactions is guaranteed to be a stationary point at $\tilde{\mathcal{Q}}^{*}$ if all elements of $\tilde{\mathcal{Q}}^{*}$ are positive, which we formally discuss in Theorem 5 in the supplementary material.
In the following, we refer to the proposed methods as EM + included structures. The symbol ' N ' indicates the adaptive noise term, e.g., EMCPTTN defines the mixture of CP, TT, and a noise term.

# 4.2 Scalability of EM tensor learning 

Since the tensor to be optimized in the M-step is given by $\mathcal{M}_{4 \boldsymbol{r}}^{k}=\mathcal{T}_{t} \Phi_{4 \boldsymbol{r}}^{k}$, we can leverage the sparsity of the input tensor $\mathcal{T}$ to make the proposed framework scalable with respect to the dimension $D$ of the data, except in the case of EMTucker, which involves the dense core tensor $\mathcal{G}$.
Specifically, in Equations (3)-(5), we can replace $\sum_{\boldsymbol{i} \in \Omega_{T}}$ with $\sum_{\boldsymbol{i} \in \Omega_{T}^{n}}$ where $\Omega_{T}^{n}$ is the set of indices of nonzero values of the tensor $\mathcal{T}$. The resulting computational time complexity is $O(\gamma N D R)$ for EMCP and $O\left(\gamma D N R^{D}\right)$ for EMTucker and EMTrain, respectively, where $N$ is the number of nonzero values, $\gamma$ is the number of iteration, assuming ranks are $(R, \ldots, R)$ for all low-rank models.
Furthermore, we reduce the computational cost of the EMTrain decomposition to $O\left(\gamma D N R^{2}\right)$ by computing the sum over the hidden variables $\boldsymbol{r} \in \Omega_{R}$ as follows. Firstly, we introduce the following tensors

$$
\mathcal{G}_{i_{1}, \ldots, i_{d}, r_{d}}^{(\rightarrow d)}=\sum_{r_{d-1}} \mathcal{G}_{i_{1}, \ldots, i_{d-1}, r_{d-1}}^{(\rightarrow d-1)} \mathcal{G}_{r_{d-1} i_{d} r_{d}}^{(d)}, \quad \mathcal{G}_{i_{d+1}, \ldots, i_{D}, r_{d}}^{(\rightarrow d)}=\sum_{r_{d+1}} \mathcal{G}_{r_{d} i_{d+1} r_{d+1}}^{(d+1 \leftarrow) \mathcal{G}_{i_{d+2}, \ldots, i_{D}, r_{d+1}}^{(d+1 \leftarrow)}
$$

with $\mathcal{G}^{(\rightarrow 1)}=\mathcal{G}^{(1)}, \mathcal{G}^{(D-1 \leftarrow)}=\mathcal{G}^{(D)}$, and $\mathcal{G}^{(\rightarrow 0)}=\mathcal{G}^{(D \leftarrow)}=1$. Each complexity is $O\left(R_{d}\right)$ to get $\mathcal{G}^{(\rightarrow d)}$ and $\mathcal{G}^{(d \leftarrow)}$ when we compute them in the order of $\mathcal{G}^{(\rightarrow 2)}, \mathcal{G}^{(\rightarrow 3)}, \ldots, \mathcal{G}^{(\rightarrow D)}$, and $\mathcal{G}^{(D-2 \leftarrow)}, \mathcal{G}^{(D-3 \leftarrow)}, \ldots, \mathcal{G}^{(1 \leftarrow)}$, respectively. The low-rank tensor $\mathcal{P}$ can be written as $\mathcal{P}=$ $\mathcal{G}^{(\rightarrow D)}=\mathcal{G}^{(0 \leftarrow)}$. Then, the update rule can be written as

$$
\mathcal{G}_{r_{d-1} i_{d} r_{d}}^{(\rightarrow d)}=\frac{\sum_{\boldsymbol{i} \in \Omega_{T, i_{d}}^{n / d}} \frac{\mathcal{T}_{t}}{\mathcal{P}_{t}} \mathcal{G}_{i_{1}, \ldots, i_{d-1}, r_{d-1}}^{(\rightarrow d-1)} \mathcal{G}_{r_{d-1} i_{d} r_{d}}^{(d) \mathcal{G}_{i_{d+1}, \ldots, i_{D}, r_{d}}^{(d \leftarrow)}}{\sum_{\boldsymbol{i} \in \Omega_{T}^{n}} \frac{\mathcal{T}_{t}}{\mathcal{P}_{t}} \mathcal{G}_{i_{1}, \ldots, i_{d}, r_{d}}^{(\rightarrow d) \mathcal{G}_{i_{d+1}, \ldots, i_{D}, r_{d}}^{(d \leftarrow)}}
$$

for $\Omega_{T, i_{d}}^{n / d}=\Omega_{T}^{n} \cap\left[I_{1}\right] \times \cdots \times\left[I_{d-1}\right] \times\left\{i_{d}\right\} \times\left[I_{d+1}\right] \cdots \times\left[I_{D}\right]$. We used the relation $\mathcal{M}_{4 \boldsymbol{r}}=\mathcal{T}_{t} \Phi_{4 \boldsymbol{r}}$ and $\Phi_{4 \boldsymbol{r}}=\mathcal{Q}_{4 \boldsymbol{r}} / \mathcal{P}_{t}$ to get the above update rule. Not all elements in Equation (13) are necessary for updating the tensors by Equation (14). Since the number of elements in $\Omega^{n}$ is $N$, the resulting complexity is $O\left(\gamma D N R^{2}\right)$. We provide the above procedure of EMTrain in Algorithm 2 in the supplementary material.
While we in the above discussed the computational complexity of the EM low-rank approximation without a mixture, specifically when $K=1$, it is straightforward to see that the complexity for $K>1$ is simply the sum of the complexity of each of the EM low-rank approximations used in the mixture.
As seen above, the developed algorithm eliminates the complexity of $I^{D}$, achieving scalability that is proportional to the number of non-zero values $N$ thus making it suitable for high-dimensional data. When applied to data with many samples, i.e. a very large $N$, the proposed method can be scaled using a batched EM approach [7].

### 4.3 EM algorithm for more general low-rank structures

We now discuss how to find the solution for the manybody approximation required in the M-step when a more complex low-rank structure is assumed in the model. By the basic property of the logarithm function, the function $L_{\mathrm{MBA}}$ to be optimized in the M-step can be decoupled into independent solvable parts with closed form. As an example, we here see the tensor network state described in Figure 4, which is known as a typical tensor tree structure [38]. The objective function of many-body approximation in the M-step can be decoupled as follows:

$$
L_{\mathrm{MBA}}(\mathcal{M} ; \mathcal{Q})=L_{\mathrm{MBA}}\left(\mathcal{M}^{\text {Tucker }} ; \mathcal{Q}^{\text {Tucker }}\right)+L_{\mathrm{MBA}}\left(\mathcal{M}^{\mathrm{TT}} ; \mathcal{Q}^{\mathrm{TT}}\right)
$$

where we define $\mathcal{M}_{i_{1} i_{2} r_{1} r_{2} r_{0}}^{\text {Tucker }}=\sum_{i_{3} i_{4} r_{3} r_{4} r_{0}} \mathcal{M}_{4 r}$ and $\mathcal{M}_{i_{3} i_{4} r_{3} r_{4} r_{0}}^{\mathrm{TT}}=\sum_{i_{1} i_{2} r_{1} r_{2} r_{0}} \mathcal{M}_{4 r}$. We can optimize both terms in the final line by the closed-form solution introduced in Section 3.1. We provide theoretical support for this procedure, including normalization conditions, in Section C. 1 in the supplementary material. By decoupling the problem with CP, Tucker, and Tensor Train decompositions, our approach approximates tensors with a wide variety of low-rank structures.

# 5 Numerical Experiments 

We empirically examined the effectiveness of our framework. While the proposed framework can explore a variety of low-rank structures and their mixtures, we here focus on the performance of EMCP, EMTrain, and their mixture EMCPTT, both with and without adaptive noise terms, due to their scalable properties. In all of the following experiments, the discrete samples are divided into $70 \%$ training, $15 \%$ validation, and $15 \%$ test samples to form training, validation, and test tensors, respectively. Tensor ranks are tuned so that the low-rank tensor reconstructed from the training tensor by the proposed or baseline method best approximates the validation tensor. The setup is more detailed in Section E in the supplementary material.
Experiments with synthetic data We verify the practical usefulness of the mixture of tensor models in an experimental setup where a synthetic low-rank true distribution is given. We synthesize fifth-order tensors with rank-8 CP and rank-4 train structures from uniform distributions, respectively, and regard them as the true distributions. Using EMCPN, EMTTN, and EMCPTTN, we estimate the true distributions from the samples generated by the true low-rank tensors and evaluate the KL errors from the true distribution to the estimated distribution. The results in Figure 5(top) illustrate that if the low-rank structure of the model and the true distribution are consistent, the proposed method can estimate the true distribution given a sufficient number of samples. Furthermore, we confirm that the mixture model EMCPTTN approximates the true distribution well, whether the true tensor has a CP or train structure.
Classification with real datasets We download eight real-world categorical datasets from the repositories described in Table 2 and conduct classification by estimated density, following the procedure described in Section E. We compared our approach to the five baseline methods: pairwise marginalized method (CNMF) [26], KL-based TT (KLTrain) [21], EMCP [24, 65], support vector classifycation (SVC), and the tensor-based Born machine as linear classification models [16]. In Table 1, we see that EMCPTTN has the best classification accuracy on all datasets except GermanGSS. # 6 Conclusion 

While it is a well-established principle that both real- and complex-valued tensors can be approximated with various low-rank structures based on local singular value decomposition (SVD), a unified framework for non-negative low-rank approximation has not been developed. Consequently, nonnegative tensor factorizations typically require piecemeal tailored implementations or gradient methods. This study introduces an EM-based unified framework that decouples the non-negative low-rank structure into multiple solvable many-body approximations and applies a closed-form solution locally, thereby eliminating the need for gradient methods. Our framework not only uniformly handles various low-rank structures but also supports adaptive noise terms and mixtures of low-rank tensors without losing the convergence guarantee. The flexibility of our modeling stems from the generality of the EM algorithm and a formulation that can take advantage of the logarithmic function properties that appear in the KL divergence. Empirical results demonstrate that our framework overall achieves superior generalization performance in classification and density estimation tasks compared to the considered baseline methods.
