## A. 1 Proofs for exact solutions of many-body approximation

First, we show the known solution formulas for the best CP rank-1 approximation that globally minimizes the KL divergence from the given tensor.
Theorem 1 (Optimal M-step in CP decomposition [24]). For a given non-negative tensor $\mathcal{M} \in$ $\mathbb{R}_{\geq 0}^{I_{1} \times \cdots \times I_{D} \times R}$, its many body approximation with interactions as described in Figure 3(a) is given as

$$
A_{i_{d} r}^{(d)}=\frac{\sum_{\boldsymbol{i} \in \Omega_{I}^{\prime} d} \mathcal{M}_{\boldsymbol{i} r}}{\mu^{1 / D}\left(\sum_{\boldsymbol{i} \in \Omega_{I}} \mathcal{M}_{\boldsymbol{i} r}\right)^{1-1 / D}}, \quad \mu=\sum_{\boldsymbol{i} \in \Omega_{I}} \sum_{r \in \Omega_{R}} \mathcal{M}_{\boldsymbol{i} r}
$$

Proof. Please refer to the original paper by Huang and Sidiropoulos [24].
In the following, we provide proofs of the closed-form solutions of many-body approximation in Figure 3(b) and (c). When a factor in a low-body tensor is multiplied by $\nu$, the value of the objective function of many-body approximation remains the same if another factor is multiplied by $1 / \nu$, which we call the scaling redundancy. The key idea in the following proofs is reducing the scaling redundancy and absorbing the normalizing conditions of the entire tensor into a single factor. This enables the decoupling of the normalized condition of the entire tensor into independent conditions about factors. This trick is also used in Section C. 1 to decouple more complicated low-rank structures into a combination of CP, Tucker, and Train decompositions.
Theorem 2 (The optimal M-step in Tucker decomposition). For a given tensor $\mathcal{M} \in$ $\mathbb{R}_{\geq 0}^{I_{1} \times \cdots I_{D} \times R_{1} \times \cdots \times R_{D}}$, its many-body approximation with the interaction described in Figure 3(b) is given as

$$
\mathcal{G}_{\boldsymbol{r}}=\frac{\sum_{\boldsymbol{i} \in \Omega_{I}} \mathcal{M}_{\boldsymbol{i} \boldsymbol{r}}}{\sum_{\boldsymbol{i} \in \Omega_{I}} \sum_{\boldsymbol{r} \in \Omega_{R}} \mathcal{M}_{\boldsymbol{i} \boldsymbol{r}}}, \quad A_{i_{d} r_{d}}^{(d)}=\frac{\sum_{\boldsymbol{i} \in \Omega_{I}^{\prime} d} \sum_{\boldsymbol{r} \in \Omega_{R}^{\prime} d} \mathcal{M}_{\boldsymbol{i} \boldsymbol{r}}}{\sum_{\boldsymbol{i} \in \Omega_{I}} \sum_{\boldsymbol{r} \in \Omega_{R}^{\prime} d} \mathcal{M}_{\boldsymbol{i} \boldsymbol{r}}}
$$

Proof. The objective function of the many-body approximation is

$$
L_{\mathrm{MBA}}\left(\mathcal{M} ; \mathcal{Q}^{\text {Tucker }}\right)=\sum_{\boldsymbol{i} \in \Omega_{I}} \sum_{\boldsymbol{r} \in \Omega_{R}} \mathcal{M}_{\boldsymbol{i} \boldsymbol{r}} \log \mathcal{Q}_{\boldsymbol{i} \boldsymbol{r}}^{\text {Tucker }}
$$

where

$$
\mathcal{Q}_{i_{1} \ldots i_{D} r_{1} \ldots r_{D}}^{\text {Tucker }}=\mathcal{G}_{r_{1} \ldots r_{D}} A_{i_{1} r_{1}}^{(1)} \ldots A_{i_{D} r_{D}}^{(D)}
$$

Since many-body approximation parameterizes tensors as discrete probability distributions, we optimize the above objective function with normalizing condition $\sum_{\boldsymbol{i} \in \Omega_{I}} \sum_{\boldsymbol{r} \in \Omega_{R}} \mathcal{Q}_{\boldsymbol{i} \boldsymbol{r}}^{\text {Tucker }}=1$. Then, we consider the following Lagrange function:

$$
\mathcal{L}=\sum_{\boldsymbol{i} \in \Omega_{I}} \sum_{\boldsymbol{r} \in \Omega_{R}} \mathcal{M}_{\boldsymbol{i} \boldsymbol{r}} \log \mathcal{G}_{\boldsymbol{r}} A_{i_{1} r_{1}}^{(1)} \ldots A_{i_{D} r_{D}}^{(D)}-\lambda\left(\sum_{\boldsymbol{i} \in \Omega_{I}} \sum_{\boldsymbol{r} \in \Omega_{R}} \mathcal{G}_{\boldsymbol{r}} A_{i_{1} r_{1}}^{(1)} \ldots A_{i_{D} r_{D}}^{(D)}-1\right)
$$

To reduce the scaling redundancy and decouple the normalizing condition, we introduce scaled factor matrices $\tilde{A}^{(d)}$ as

$$
\tilde{A}_{i_{d} r_{d}}^{(d)}=\frac{A_{i_{d} r_{d}}^{(d)}}{a_{r_{d}}^{(d)}}, \quad \text { where } a_{r_{d}}^{(d)}=\sum_{i_{d}} A_{i_{d} r_{d}}
$$

for $d=1,2, \ldots, D$ and the scaled core tensor,

$$
\tilde{\mathcal{G}}_{\boldsymbol{r}}=\mathcal{G}_{\boldsymbol{r}} a_{r_{1}}^{(1)} \ldots a_{r_{D}}^{(D)}
$$

The normalizing condition $\sum_{i \in \Omega_{I}} \sum_{r \in \Omega_{R}} \mathcal{Q}_{i r}^{\text {Tucker }}=1$ guarantees the normalization of the core tensor $\tilde{\mathcal{G}}$ as

$$
\sum_{r \in \Omega_{R}} \tilde{\mathcal{G}}_{r}=1
$$

The tensor $\mathcal{Q}^{\text {Tucker }}$ can be represented with the scaled matrices $\tilde{A}^{(d)}$ and core tensor $\tilde{\mathcal{G}}$ introduced above as

$$
\mathcal{Q}_{i r}^{\text {Tucker }}=\mathcal{G}_{r} A_{i_{1} r_{1}}^{(1)} \ldots A_{i_{D} r_{D}}^{(D)}=\tilde{\mathcal{G}}_{r} \tilde{A}_{i_{1} r_{1}}^{(1)} \ldots \tilde{A}_{i_{D} r_{D}}^{(D)}
$$

We optimize $\tilde{\mathcal{G}}$ and $\tilde{A}_{i_{d} r_{d}}^{(d)}$ instead of $\mathcal{G}$ and $A_{i_{d} r_{d}}^{(d)}$. Thus the Lagrange function can be written as

$$
\mathcal{L}=\sum_{i \in \Omega_{I}} \sum_{r \in \Omega_{R}} \mathcal{M}_{i r} \log \tilde{\mathcal{G}}_{r} \tilde{A}_{i_{1} r_{1}}^{(1)} \ldots \tilde{A}_{i_{D} r_{D}}^{(D)}-\lambda\left(\sum_{r} \tilde{\mathcal{G}}_{r}-1\right)-\sum_{d=1}^{D} \sum_{r_{d}} \lambda_{r_{d}}^{(d)}\left(\sum_{r_{d}} \tilde{A}_{i_{d} r_{d}}^{(d)}-1\right)
$$

The condition

$$
\frac{\partial \mathcal{L}}{\partial \tilde{\mathcal{G}}_{r}}=\frac{\partial \mathcal{L}}{\partial \tilde{A}_{i_{d} r_{d}}^{(d)}}=0
$$

leads the optimal core tensor and factor matrices

$$
\tilde{\mathcal{G}}_{r}=\frac{1}{\lambda} \sum_{i \in \Omega_{I}} \mathcal{M}_{i r}, \quad \tilde{A}_{i_{d} r_{d}}^{(d)}=\frac{1}{\lambda_{r_{d}}^{(d)}} \sum_{i \in \Omega_{I}^{\prime d}} \sum_{r \in \Omega_{R}^{\prime d}} \mathcal{M}_{i r}
$$

The values of Lagrange multipliers are obtained by the normalizing conditions (16) and (17) as

$$
\lambda=\sum_{i \in \Omega_{I}} \sum_{r \in \Omega_{R}} \mathcal{M}_{i r}, \quad \lambda_{r_{d}}^{(d)}=\sum_{i \in \Omega_{I}} \sum_{r \in \Omega_{R}^{\prime d}} \mathcal{M}_{i r}
$$

Theorem 3 (The optimal M-step in Train decomposition). For a given tensor $\mathcal{M} \in$ $\mathbb{R}_{\geq 0}^{I_{1} \times \cdots \times I_{D} \times R_{1} \times \cdots \times R_{D-1}}$, its many-body approximation with interactions described in Figure 3(c) is given as

$$
\mathcal{G}_{r_{d-1} i_{d} r_{d}}^{(d)}=\frac{\sum_{i \in \Omega_{I}^{\prime d}} \sum_{r \in \Omega_{R}^{\prime d, d-1}} \mathcal{M}_{i r}}{\sum_{i \in \Omega_{I}} \sum_{r \in \Omega_{R}^{\prime d}} \mathcal{M}_{i r}}
$$

for $d=1, \ldots, D$, assuming $r_{0}=r_{D}=1$.
Proof. The objective function of the many-body approximation is

$$
L_{\mathrm{MBA}}\left(\mathcal{M} ; \mathcal{Q}^{\mathrm{Train}}\right)=\sum_{i \in \Omega_{I}} \sum_{r \in \Omega_{R}} \mathcal{M}_{i r} \log \mathcal{Q}_{i r}^{\mathrm{Train}}
$$

where

$$
\mathcal{Q}_{i_{1} \ldots i_{D} r_{1} \ldots r_{D}}^{\mathrm{Train}}=\mathcal{G}_{i_{1} r_{1}}^{(1)} \mathcal{G}_{r_{1} i_{2} r_{2}}^{(2)} \ldots \mathcal{G}_{r_{D-1} i_{D}}^{(D)}
$$

Since many-body approximation parameterizes tensors as discrete probability distributions, we optimize the above objective function with normalizing condition $\sum_{i \in \Omega_{I}} \sum_{r \in \Omega_{R}} \mathcal{Q}_{i r}^{\text {Train }}=1$. Then, we consider the following Lagrange function:

$$
\mathcal{L}=\sum_{i \in \Omega_{I}} \sum_{r \in \Omega_{R}} \mathcal{M}_{i r} \log \mathcal{G}_{i_{1} r_{1}}^{(1)} \mathcal{G}_{r_{1} i_{2} r_{2}}^{(2)} \ldots \mathcal{G}_{r_{D-1} i_{D}}^{(D)}-\lambda\left(\sum_{i \in \Omega_{I}} \sum_{r \in \Omega_{R}} \mathcal{G}_{i_{1} r_{1}}^{(1)} \mathcal{G}_{r_{1} i_{2} r_{2}}^{(2)} \ldots \mathcal{G}_{r_{D-1} i_{D}}^{(D)}-1\right)
$$

To decouple the normalizing condition and make the problem simpler, we introduce scaled core tensors $\tilde{\mathcal{G}}^{(1)}, \ldots, \tilde{\mathcal{G}}^{(D-1)}$ that are normalized over $r_{d-1}$ and $i_{d}$ as

$$
\tilde{\mathcal{G}}_{r_{d-1} i_{d} r_{d}}^{(d)}=\frac{g_{r_{d-1}}^{(d-1)}}{g_{r_{d}}^{(d)}} \mathcal{G}_{r_{d-1} i_{d} r_{d}}^{(d)}
$$

where we define

$$
g_{r_{d}}^{(d)}=\sum_{r_{d-1}} \sum_{i_{d}} \mathcal{G}_{r_{d-1} i_{d} r_{d}}^{(d)} g_{r_{d-1}}^{(d-1)}
$$

with $g_{r_{0}}=1$. We assume $r_{0}=r_{D}=1$. Using the scaled core tensors, the tensor $\mathcal{Q}^{\text {Train }}$ can be written as

$$
\hat{\mathcal{G}}_{i_{1} \ldots i_{D} r_{1} \ldots r_{D}}^{\text {Train }}=\mathcal{G}_{i_{1} r_{1}}^{(1)} \mathcal{G}_{r_{1} i_{2} r_{2}}^{(2)} \ldots \mathcal{G}_{r_{D-1} i_{D}}^{(D)}=\hat{\mathcal{G}}_{i_{1} r_{1}}^{(1)} \hat{\mathcal{G}}_{r_{1} i_{2} r_{2}}^{(2)} \ldots \hat{\mathcal{G}}_{r_{D-1} i_{D}}^{(D)}
$$

with

$$
\hat{\mathcal{G}}_{r_{D-1} i_{D}}^{(D)}=\frac{1}{g_{r_{D-1}}^{(D-1)}} \mathcal{G}_{r_{D-1} i_{D}}^{(D)}
$$

The matrix $\hat{\mathcal{G}}^{(D)}$ is normalized, satisfying $\sum_{r_{D-1}} \sum_{i_{D}} \hat{\mathcal{G}}_{r_{D-1} i_{D}}^{(D)}=1$. Thus, the Lagrange function can be written as

$$
\begin{aligned}
\mathcal{L}=\sum_{\boldsymbol{i} \in \Omega_{I}} \sum_{\boldsymbol{r} \in \Omega_{R}} \mathcal{M}_{\boldsymbol{i} \boldsymbol{r}} \log \hat{\mathcal{G}}_{i_{1} r_{1}}^{(1)} \hat{\mathcal{G}}_{r_{1} i_{2} r_{2}}^{(2)} \ldots \hat{\mathcal{G}}_{r_{D-1} i_{D}}^{(D)} & -\sum_{d=1}^{D-1} \lambda_{r_{d}}^{(d)}\left(\sum_{r_{d-1}} \sum_{i_{d}} \hat{\mathcal{G}}_{r_{d-1} i_{d} r_{d}}^{(d)}-1\right) \\
& -\lambda^{(D)}\left(\sum_{r_{D-1}} \sum_{i_{d}} \hat{\mathcal{G}}_{r_{D-1} i_{D}}^{(D)}-1\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

The critical condition

$$
\frac{\partial \mathcal{L}}{\partial \hat{\mathcal{G}}_{r_{d-1} i_{d} r_{d}}^{(d)}}=0
$$

leads the optimal core tensors

$$
\hat{\mathcal{G}}_{r_{d-1} i_{d} r_{d}}^{(d)}=\frac{1}{\lambda_{r_{d}}^{(d)}} \sum_{\boldsymbol{i} \in \Omega_{I}^{\prime d}} \sum_{\boldsymbol{r} \in \Omega_{R}^{\prime d, d-1}} \mathcal{M}_{\boldsymbol{i} \boldsymbol{r}}
$$

where the values of multipliers are identified by the normalizing conditions in Equation (19) as

$$
\lambda_{r_{d}}^{(d)}=\sum_{\boldsymbol{i} \in \Omega_{I}} \sum_{\boldsymbol{r} \in \Omega_{R}^{\prime d}} \mathcal{M}_{\boldsymbol{i} \boldsymbol{r}}
$$

# A. 2 Proofs for EM-algorithm 

We prove the propositions used to derive the EM algorithm for non-negative tensor mixture learning in Section 4. Furthermore, we show the convergence of the proposed method in Theorem 4.
Proposition 1. For any tensors $\Phi^{1}, \ldots, \Phi^{K}$ that satisfies $\sum_{k=1}^{K} \sum_{\boldsymbol{r} \in \Omega_{R^{k}}} \Phi_{\boldsymbol{i} \boldsymbol{r}}^{k}=1$, the cross entropy $L(\hat{\mathcal{Q}})$ in Equation (7) can be bounded as follows:

$$
L(\hat{\mathcal{Q}}) \geq \bar{L}(\hat{\mathcal{Q}}, \Phi)=\sum_{\boldsymbol{i} \in \Omega_{I}} \sum_{k=1}^{K} \sum_{\boldsymbol{r} \in \Omega_{R^{k}}} \mathcal{T}_{\boldsymbol{i}} \Phi_{\boldsymbol{i} \boldsymbol{r}}^{k} \log \frac{\hat{\mathcal{Q}}_{\boldsymbol{i} \boldsymbol{r}}^{k}}{\Phi_{\boldsymbol{i} \boldsymbol{r}}^{k}}
$$

Proof. For any tensors $\Phi^{1}, \ldots, \Phi^{K}$ that satisfies $\sum_{k=1}^{K} \sum_{\boldsymbol{r} \in \Omega_{R^{k}}} \Phi_{\boldsymbol{i} \boldsymbol{r}}^{k}=1$, we can transform the cross entropy $L(\hat{\mathcal{Q}})$ as follows:

$$
\begin{aligned}
L(\hat{\mathcal{Q}}) & =\sum_{\boldsymbol{i} \in \Omega_{I}} \mathcal{T}_{\boldsymbol{i}} \log \mathcal{P}_{\boldsymbol{i}} \\
& =\sum_{\boldsymbol{i} \in \Omega_{I}} \mathcal{T}_{\boldsymbol{i}} \log \sum_{\boldsymbol{r} \in \Omega_{R^{k}}} \hat{\mathcal{Q}}_{\boldsymbol{i} \boldsymbol{r}}^{k} \\
& =\sum_{\boldsymbol{i} \in \Omega_{I}} \mathcal{T}_{\boldsymbol{i}} \log \sum_{k=1}^{K} \sum_{\boldsymbol{r} \in \Omega_{R^{k}}} \frac{\Phi_{\boldsymbol{i} \boldsymbol{r}}^{k} \hat{\mathcal{Q}}_{\boldsymbol{i} \boldsymbol{r}}^{k}}{\Phi_{\boldsymbol{i} \boldsymbol{r}}^{k}} \\
& \geq \sum_{\boldsymbol{i} \in \Omega_{I}} \sum_{k=1}^{K} \sum_{\boldsymbol{r} \in \Omega_{R^{k}}} \mathcal{T}_{\boldsymbol{i}} \Phi_{\boldsymbol{i} \boldsymbol{r}}^{k} \log \frac{\hat{\mathcal{Q}}_{\boldsymbol{i} \boldsymbol{r}}^{k}}{\Phi_{\boldsymbol{i} \boldsymbol{r}}^{k}}=\bar{L}(\mathcal{Q}, \Phi)
\end{aligned}
$$

where the following relation, called the Jensen inequality [28], is used:

$$
f\left(\sum_{m=1}^{M} \lambda_{m} x_{m}\right) \geq \sum_{m=1}^{M} \lambda_{m} f\left(x_{m}\right)
$$

for any concave function $f: \mathbb{R} \rightarrow \mathbb{R}$ and real numbers $\lambda_{1}, \ldots, \lambda_{M}$ that satisfies $\sum_{m=1}^{M} \lambda_{m}=1$. The inequality is adaptable in Equation (21) because the logarithm function is a concave function.
Proposition 2. In E-step, the optimal update for $\Phi$ is given as

$$
\hat{\Phi}_{i r}^{k}=\frac{\hat{\mathcal{Q}}_{i r}^{k}}{\sum_{k=1}^{K} \sum_{r \in \Omega_{R^{k}}} \hat{\mathcal{Q}}_{i r}^{k}}
$$

Proof. We put Equation (10) into the lower bound $\bar{L}$ in Equation (8),

$$
\begin{aligned}
\bar{L}(\hat{\mathcal{Q}}, \hat{\Phi}) & =\sum_{i \in \Omega_{I}} \sum_{k=1}^{K} \sum_{r \in \Omega_{R^{k}}} \mathcal{T}_{i} \hat{\Phi}_{i r}^{k} \log \frac{\hat{\mathcal{Q}}_{i r}^{k}}{\hat{\Phi}_{i r}^{k}} \\
& =\sum_{i \in \Omega_{I}} \sum_{k=1}^{K} \sum_{r \in \Omega_{R^{k}}} \mathcal{T}_{i} \sum_{k=1}^{K} \sum_{\sum_{r \in \Omega_{R^{k}}} \in \Omega_{R^{k}}} \hat{\mathcal{Q}}_{i r}^{k} \log \sum_{k=1}^{K} \sum_{r \in \Omega_{R^{k}}} \hat{\mathcal{Q}}_{i r}^{k} \\
& =\sum_{i \in \Omega_{I}} \mathcal{T}_{i} \log \sum_{k=1}^{K} \sum_{r \in \Omega_{R^{k}}} \hat{\mathcal{Q}}_{i r}^{k} \\
& =L(\hat{\mathcal{Q}})
\end{aligned}
$$

Jensen's inequality in Equation (22) shows that

$$
L(\hat{\mathcal{Q}})=\bar{L}(\hat{\mathcal{Q}}, \hat{\Phi}) \geq \bar{L}(\hat{\mathcal{Q}}, \Phi)
$$

for any tensors $\Phi \in \mathcal{D}$ where $\mathcal{D}=\left\{\left(\Phi^{1}, \ldots, \Phi^{K}\right) \mid \sum_{k} \sum_{r \in \Omega_{R^{k}}} \Phi_{i r}^{k}=1\right\}$. Thus, the tensors $\hat{\Phi}=\left(\hat{\Phi}^{1}, \ldots, \hat{\Phi}^{K}\right)$ are optimal.
Proposition 3. In M-step, the optimal update for the mixture ratio $\eta=\left(\eta^{1}, \ldots, \eta^{K}\right)$ that optimizes $J(\eta)$ in Equation (9) is given as

$$
\eta^{k}=\frac{\sum_{i \in \Omega_{I}} \sum_{r \in \Omega_{R^{k}}} \mathcal{T}_{i} \Phi_{i r}^{k}}{\sum_{i \in \Omega_{I}} \sum_{k=1}^{K} \sum_{r \in \Omega_{R^{k}}} \mathcal{T}_{i} \Phi_{i r}^{k}}
$$

Proof. We optimize the decoupled objective function

$$
J(\eta)=\sum_{i \in \Omega_{I}} \sum_{k=1}^{K} \sum_{r \in \Omega_{R^{k}}} \mathcal{T}_{i} \Phi_{i r}^{k} \log \eta^{k}
$$

with conditions $\sum_{k=1}^{K} \eta^{k}=1$ and $\eta^{k} \geq 0$. Thus we consider the following Lagrange function

$$
\mathcal{L}=\sum_{i \in \Omega_{I}} \sum_{k=1}^{K} \sum_{r \in \Omega_{R^{k}}} \mathcal{T}_{i} \Phi_{i r}^{k} \log \eta^{k}-\lambda\left(\sum_{k=1}^{K} \eta^{k}-1\right)
$$

The condition $\partial \mathcal{L} / \partial \eta^{k}=0$ leads to the optimal ratio

$$
\eta^{k}=\frac{1}{\lambda} \sum_{i \in \Omega_{I}} \sum_{r \in \Omega_{R^{k}}} \mathcal{T}_{i} \Phi_{i r}^{k}
$$

where the multiplier $\lambda$ is given as

$$
\lambda=\sum_{i \in \Omega_{I}} \sum_{k=1}^{K} \sum_{r \in \Omega_{R^{k}}} \mathcal{T}_{i} \Phi_{i r}^{k}
$$

To the best of our knowledge, the general convergence theorem of the MU method is still an open problem, requiring proof of convergence for each minor change in the objective function, such as varying the low-rank structure or adding a regularization term. On the other hand, the following Theorem 4 ensures that our framework converges regardless of such variations of the object function.
Theorem 4. The objective function of the mixture EM-tensor factorization always converges regardless of the choice of low-rank structure and mixtures.
Proof. We prove the convergence of the EM algorithm from the fact that the objective function $L$ is bounded above and that the E-step and M-step maximize the lower bound $\bar{L}$ with respect to $\Phi$ and $\hat{\mathcal{Q}}$, respectively. The E-step in iteration $t$ updates $\Phi^{t-1}$ by optimal $\hat{\Phi}^{t}$ to maximize the lower bound for $\Phi$ such as

$$
L\left(\hat{\mathcal{Q}}^{t}\right)=\bar{L}\left(\hat{\mathcal{Q}}^{t}, \tilde{\Phi}^{t}\right) \geq \bar{L}\left(\hat{\mathcal{Q}}^{t}, \Phi^{t-1}\right)
$$

Then, the M-step in iteration $t$ updates $\hat{\mathcal{Q}}^{t}$ by $\hat{\mathcal{Q}}^{t+1}$ to maximize the lower bound for $\hat{\mathcal{Q}}$ such as

$$
\bar{L}\left(\hat{\mathcal{Q}}^{t+1}, \tilde{\Phi}^{t}\right) \geq \bar{L}\left(\hat{\mathcal{Q}}^{t}, \hat{\Phi}^{t}\right)
$$

Again, the E-step in iteration $t+1$ updates $\Phi^{t}$ by $\tilde{\Phi}^{t+1}$ to maximize the lower bound for $\Phi$ such as

$$
L\left(\hat{\mathcal{Q}}^{t+1}\right) \stackrel{\mathrm{Eq} .(23)}{=} \bar{L}\left(\hat{\mathcal{Q}}^{t+1}, \tilde{\Phi}_{t+1}\right) \geq \bar{L}\left(\hat{\mathcal{Q}}^{t+1}, \Phi^{t}\right)
$$

Combining the above three relations, we obtain

$$
L\left(\hat{\mathcal{Q}}^{t+1}\right)=\bar{L}\left(\hat{\mathcal{Q}}^{t+1}, \tilde{\Phi}^{t+1}\right) \geq \bar{L}\left(\hat{\mathcal{Q}}^{t+1}, \hat{\Phi}^{t}\right) \geq \bar{L}\left(\hat{\mathcal{Q}}^{t}, \tilde{\Phi}^{t}\right)=L\left(\hat{\mathcal{Q}}^{t}\right)
$$

Thus, it holds that $L\left(\hat{\mathcal{Q}}^{t+1}\right) \geq L\left(\hat{\mathcal{Q}}^{t}\right)$. Thus, the algorithm converges because the objective function is bounded above and would not be decreasing in each iteration.

# B Convergence Analysis 

The convergence of the algorithm can be analyzed by examining the behavior of the objective function at the accumulation points, which are the convergence points of subsequences of the point sequence generated by the algorithm at each step. In several matrix factorization methods, it has been shown that, under certain assumptions, the accumulation points of the sequence generated by the algorithm are stationary points of the objective function [36, 58]. By a similar analysis, we show following two propositions related to the accumulation points of the point sequences generated by our proposed method.

1. The accumulation points are included in the domain of the objective function $L$ and its lower bound $\bar{L}$
2. The Lagrange function with the objective function and constraint for interactions is a stationary point at the accumulation points if all elements of the accumulation points have positive values.

This section is organized as follows. First, we explain in Section B. 1 that we need to analyze the stationary points of the Lagrangian function, rather than the stationary points of the objective function directly, because the proposed method optimizes the objective function in the domain that satisfies constraints on nonnegativity and interactions among random variables, not in Euclidean space. Then, in Section B.2, we discuss the domain, continuity, and differentiability of the objective function and its lower bounds. In Section B.3, using the above discussion, we prove the compactness of the level set, which is assumed in typical analysis of EM algorithms, and demonstrate that the accumulation points are included in the domain of the objective function and its lower bound. Section B. 4 proves that if all element of the tensor at an accumulation point are non-zero, then the Lagrange function is a stationary point at the accumulation points.
In the following discussion, $\left\{\hat{\mathcal{Q}}^{t}\right\}_{t \in \mathbb{N}}$ and $\left\{\left(\hat{\mathcal{Q}}^{t}, \Phi^{t}\right)\right\}_{t \in \mathbb{N}}$ refers to the point sequence generated by the proposed EM algorithm, and $\hat{\mathcal{Q}}^{*}$ and $\left(\hat{\mathcal{Q}}^{*}, \Phi^{*}\right)$ refers to its accumulation points, respectively.

# B. 1 Preliminaries
## B.1.1 Conditional stationary point

In the standard discussion of EM algorithms, the probability distribution is parameterized by a parameter $\theta$ that takes real values freely, and convergence to a stationary point is guaranteed under certain assumptions by showing that the objective function $L$ satisfies $d L\left(\theta^{*}\right) / d \theta=0$ at the convergence point $\theta^{*}$. In contrast, our approach directly optimizes the value of the probability distribution while restricting the interactions among random variables, rather than introducing such real valued parameters $\theta$. Consequently, in the proposed method, the objective function $L$ is optimized with respect to variables defined on a constrained space of interactions. This necessitates discussing convergence to a stationary point in terms of differentiation on the constrained space, rather than differentiation in a conventional Euclidean space.
For this purpose, we define a stationary point in a constrained space at the stationary point of the Lagrangian function, referred to as a conditional stationary point. This definition is equivalent to a stationary point in the sense of a differentiation on a manifold when the constrained space is considered to be a manifold.
Definition 1 (Conditional stationary point). Let $f, g_{1}, g_{2}, \ldots, g_{M}$ be functions from the open set $\mathcal{U} \subset$ $\mathbb{R}^{N}$ and $\boldsymbol{\mathcal { B }}=\left\{\boldsymbol{x}=\left(x_{1}, \ldots, x_{J}\right) \in \mathcal{U} \mid g_{m}(\boldsymbol{x})=0\right.$ for all $\left.m \in[M]\right\}$. We call $\boldsymbol{x}$ the conditional stationary point of the function $f$ on $\mathcal{B}$ if there exists real numbers $\lambda_{1}, \ldots, \lambda_{M}$ that satisfies the following relation:

$$
\frac{\partial}{\partial x_{j}} f(\boldsymbol{x})=\sum_{m=1}^{M} \lambda_{m} \frac{\partial}{\partial x_{j}} g(\boldsymbol{x})
$$

The above definition coincides with the stationary points of the Lagrangian function:

$$
\mathcal{L}(\boldsymbol{x}, \boldsymbol{\lambda})=f(\boldsymbol{x})-\sum_{m=1}^{M} \lambda_{m} g_{m}(\boldsymbol{x})
$$

for optimizing the function $f(\boldsymbol{x})$ under the constraints $g_{m}(\boldsymbol{x})=0$ for $m=1,2, \ldots, M$.

## B.1.2 Inadmissible zeros

The following corollary, which we use in the remainder of this section, is immediately proved from the closed-form update rules of the proposed EM algorithm.
Corollary 1. Let $\left\{\left(\tilde{\mathcal{Q}}^{t}, \Phi^{t}\right)\right\}_{t \in \mathbb{N}}$ be the sequence generated by the EM tensor learning where $\tilde{\mathcal{Q}}^{t}=\left(\tilde{\mathcal{Q}}^{1, t}, \ldots, \tilde{\mathcal{Q}}^{K, t}\right)$ and $\Phi^{t}=\left(\Phi^{1, t}, \ldots, \Phi^{K, t}\right)$. Then it holds that $\tilde{\mathcal{Q}}_{\boldsymbol{i} \boldsymbol{r}}^{k, 0}>0 \Rightarrow \tilde{\mathcal{Q}}_{\boldsymbol{i} \boldsymbol{r}}^{k, t}>0$ and $\Phi_{\boldsymbol{i} \boldsymbol{r}}^{k, t}>0$ for any finite number $t \in \mathbb{N}$.
Proof. It is evident from the update rules in Equations (1), (4), (5), (12), and (10)
Although Corollary 1 is mathematically correct, we admit that $\tilde{\mathcal{Q}}_{\boldsymbol{i} \boldsymbol{r}}^{k, t}$ can practically be treated as 0 if the value of $\tilde{\mathcal{Q}}_{\boldsymbol{i} \boldsymbol{r}}^{k, t}$ is very small positive value, due to the limit of the number of digits that the computer can handle. From the updates rule of the EM-algorithm, we can also confirm that once the value $\tilde{\mathcal{Q}}^{k, t}$ becomes 0 , the value remains 0 throughout the algorithm. That is, $\tilde{\mathcal{Q}}_{\boldsymbol{i} \boldsymbol{r}}^{k, T}=0 \Rightarrow \tilde{\mathcal{Q}}_{\boldsymbol{i} \boldsymbol{r}}^{k, t}=0$ for any finite number $t \geq T$, which is well-discussed phenomenon called inadmissible zeros [9]. Throughout the following discussion, however, we assume that the computer can deal with a sufficiently large number of digits, and consequently Corollary 1 is satisfied.

## B. 2 Domain and Continuity of the Objective Function and its Lower Bounds
## B.2.1 Objective function

In the following, we consider approximating a given tensor $\mathcal{T} \in \mathbb{R}^{I_{1} \times \cdots \times I_{D}}$ by a mixture of $K$ low-rank tensors $\mathcal{P}=\sum_{k=1}^{K} \eta^{k} \mathcal{P}^{k}$ for $\mathcal{P}_{\boldsymbol{i}}^{k}=\sum_{\boldsymbol{r} \in \Omega_{R^{k}}} \mathcal{Q}_{\boldsymbol{i} \boldsymbol{r}}^{k}$ for $\boldsymbol{i} \in \Omega_{I}=\left[I_{1}\right] \times \cdots \times\left[I_{D}\right]$ and $\Omega_{R^{k}}=\left[R_{1}\right] \times \cdots \times\left[R_{V^{k}}\right]$.

The objective function of the EM algorithm is defined as follows:

$$
L(\hat{\mathcal{Q}})=\sum_{\boldsymbol{i} \in \Omega_{I}^{c}} \mathcal{T}_{\boldsymbol{i}} \log \sum_{k=1}^{K} \sum_{\boldsymbol{r} \in \Omega_{R^{k}}} \hat{\mathcal{Q}}_{\boldsymbol{i} \boldsymbol{r}}^{k}
$$

where the summation is over the observed indices $\Omega_{I}^{o}=\left\{\boldsymbol{i} \subset \Omega_{I} \mid \mathcal{T}_{\boldsymbol{i}} \neq 0\right\}$. We note that the normalizing condition of $\hat{\mathcal{Q}}$ makes the objective function negative or equal to 0 , that is $L(\hat{\mathcal{Q}}) \leq 0$. The $\hat{\mathcal{Q}}$ is the element of the closed set $\boldsymbol{B}$.

$$
\hat{\mathcal{Q}} \in \boldsymbol{B}=\left\{\left(\hat{\mathcal{Q}}^{1}, \ldots, \hat{\mathcal{Q}}^{K}\right) \mid \hat{\mathcal{Q}}^{k}=\eta^{k} \mathcal{Q}^{k}, \quad \sum_{k=1}^{K} \eta^{k}=1, \quad \eta_{k} \geq 0, \quad \mathcal{Q}^{k} \in \boldsymbol{B}^{k}, \quad \text { for all } k \in[K]\right\}
$$

where $\boldsymbol{B}^{k}$ is the set of normalized low-body tensors corresponding to the low-rank tensor $\mathcal{P}^{k}$. In the instance of $k=\mathrm{CP}$, it can be given as

$$
\boldsymbol{B}^{\mathrm{CP}}=\left\{\mathcal{Q}^{\mathrm{CP}} \in \mathbb{R}^{\left[\Omega_{I}\right] \times R} \mid \mathcal{Q}_{\boldsymbol{i} r}^{\mathrm{CP}}=\prod_{d=1}^{D} A_{i_{d} r}^{(d)}, \quad A_{i_{d} r}^{(d)} \in\left[0, C^{\mathrm{CP}}\right], \sum_{\boldsymbol{i} \in \Omega_{I}} \sum_{r=1}^{R} \mathcal{Q}_{\boldsymbol{i} r}^{\mathrm{CP}}=1\right\}
$$

The two-body interaction or $A^{(d)}$ is bounded by a constant $C^{\mathrm{CP}}$, which we provide an explicit representation in Equation (26) below. As a generalization of $k \in\{\mathrm{CP}$, Tucker, Train $\}$, the set $\boldsymbol{B}^{k}$ can be written as

$$
\boldsymbol{B}^{k}=\left\{\mathcal{Q}^{k} \in \mathbb{R}^{\left[\Omega_{I}\right] \times\left|\Omega_{R^{k}}\right|} \mid \mathcal{Q}_{\boldsymbol{i} \boldsymbol{r}}^{k}=\prod_{h^{k}=1}^{H^{k}} \mathcal{Z}_{\boldsymbol{v}\left(h^{k}\right)}^{k, h^{k}}, \quad \mathcal{Z}_{\boldsymbol{v}\left(h^{k}\right)}^{k, h^{k}} \in\left[0, C^{k}\right], \sum_{\boldsymbol{i} \in \Omega_{I}} \sum_{\boldsymbol{r} \in \Omega_{R^{k}}} \mathcal{Q}_{\boldsymbol{i} \boldsymbol{r}}^{k}=1\right\}
$$

where the tensor $\mathcal{Z}^{k, h^{k}}$ is the $h^{k}$-th interaction of the low-body tensor $\mathcal{Q}^{k}$ corresponding to the $k$-th low-rank tensor $\mathcal{P}^{k}$ describing the interaction among the indices $\boldsymbol{v}\left(h^{k}\right)$. Tensor $\mathcal{Q}^{k}$ consists of $H^{k}$ interactions. Suppose $V^{k}$ is the number of hidden variables that the low-rank tensor $\mathcal{P}^{k}$ has, then $\left|\Omega_{R^{k}}\right|=R_{1} \times \cdots \times R_{V^{k}}$ where $R_{v^{k}}$ is the degree of freedom of $v^{k}$-th hidden variable $r_{v^{k}}$ for $v^{k}=1,2, \ldots, V^{k}$. In short, the integers $\left(R_{1}, \ldots, R_{V^{k}}\right)$ is a generalization of CP, Tucker, and Tensor Train ranks. We refer to all of the interactions $\left\{\mathcal{Z}^{k, h^{k}}\right\}_{k, h}$ and mixing ratios $\eta=\left(\eta^{1}, \ldots, \eta^{K}\right)$ in $\hat{\mathcal{Q}}$ together as factors of $\hat{\mathcal{Q}}$. The set $\boldsymbol{B}$ is bounded because the interaction $\left\{\mathcal{Z}^{k, h^{k}}\right\}_{k, h}$ is bounded by the constant

$$
C^{k}=\left(\max _{\boldsymbol{i} \in \Omega_{I}} \mathcal{T}_{\boldsymbol{i}}\left|\Omega_{I}\right|\left|\Omega_{R^{k}}\right|\right)^{1 / H_{k}}
$$

For the discussion of the convergence of the EM algorithm, we need to care that the objective function $L(\hat{\mathcal{Q}})$ cannot be defined with $\sum_{k} \sum_{\boldsymbol{r} \in \Omega_{R^{k}}} \mathcal{Q}_{\boldsymbol{i} \boldsymbol{r}}^{k}=0$. Then, we define the domain of the objective function $L(\hat{\mathcal{Q}})$ as follows:

$$
\operatorname{dom}(L)=\left\{\hat{\mathcal{Q}} \in \boldsymbol{B} \mid \sum_{k} \sum_{\boldsymbol{r} \in \Omega_{R^{k}}} \hat{\mathcal{Q}}_{\boldsymbol{i} \boldsymbol{r}}^{k}>0 \text { for all } \boldsymbol{i} \in \Omega_{I}^{o}\right\}
$$

It is obvious that the objective function $L(\hat{\mathcal{Q}})$ is differentiable with respect to the variables $\hat{\mathcal{Q}}_{\boldsymbol{i} \boldsymbol{r}}^{k}$ over $\operatorname{dom}(L)$ for all $\boldsymbol{i} \in \Omega_{I}, \boldsymbol{r} \in \Omega_{R^{k}}$, and $k \in[K]$. Since Corollary 1 says $\hat{\mathcal{Q}}^{0} \in \operatorname{dom}(L) \Rightarrow \hat{\mathcal{Q}}^{t} \in$ $\operatorname{dom}(L)$ for any natural number $t \in \mathbb{N}$, the objective function $L(\hat{\mathcal{Q}})$ is differentiable by any factor of $\hat{\mathcal{Q}}$ throughout the EM algorithm using the chain rule.

# B.2.2 The lower bound of the objective function 

The lower-bound of the objective function $L$ is given as

$$
\bar{L}(\hat{\mathcal{Q}}, \Phi)=\sum_{k=1}^{K} \sum_{(\boldsymbol{i}, \boldsymbol{r}) \in \Omega_{I^{k}}^{c}} \mathcal{T}_{\boldsymbol{i}} \Phi_{\boldsymbol{i} \boldsymbol{r}}^{k} \log \frac{\hat{\mathcal{Q}}_{\boldsymbol{i} \boldsymbol{r}}^{k}}{\Phi_{\boldsymbol{i} \boldsymbol{r}}^{k}}
$$

where the summation is over the indices $\Omega_{I R^{k}}^{o}=\left\{(\boldsymbol{i}, \boldsymbol{r}) \in \Omega_{I}^{o} \times \Omega_{R^{k}} \mid \Phi_{i \boldsymbol{r}}^{k}>0\right\}$ and tensors $\Phi=\left(\Phi^{1}, \ldots, \Phi^{K}\right)$ are in the closed set $\mathcal{D}$.

$$
\mathcal{D}=\left\{\left(\Phi^{1}, \ldots, \Phi^{K}\right) \mid \sum_{k} \sum_{\boldsymbol{r} \in \Omega_{R^{k}}} \Phi_{i \boldsymbol{r}}^{k}=1 \text { and } \Phi_{i \boldsymbol{r}}^{k} \geq 0 \text { for any } \boldsymbol{i} \in \Omega_{I}, \boldsymbol{r} \in \Omega_{R^{k}}, k \in[K]\right\}
$$

The above definition of the lower bound in Equation (27) is equivalent to Equation (8) because we can replace $\sum_{m}$ with $\sum_{m(\neq l)}$ if $\lambda_{l}=0$ in Jensen's inequality in Equation (22).
The upper bound cannot be defined when it holds that $\dot{\mathcal{Q}}_{\boldsymbol{i r}}^{k}=0$ and $\Phi_{\boldsymbol{i r}}^{k}>0$. Then, we define the domain of the lower bound $\bar{L}$ as

$$
\operatorname{dom}(\bar{L})=\left\{(\dot{\mathcal{Q}}, \Phi) \in \boldsymbol{\mathcal { B }} \times \mathcal{D} \mid \dot{\mathcal{Q}}_{\boldsymbol{i r}}^{k}>0 \text { if } \Phi_{\boldsymbol{i r}}^{k}>0 \text { for all } \boldsymbol{i} \in \Omega_{I}^{o}\right\}
$$

Although the lower-bound $\bar{L}(\dot{\mathcal{Q}}, \Phi)$ is not continuous as a function of $(\dot{\mathcal{Q}}, \Phi)$, it is partial differentiable with $\dot{\mathcal{Q}}$ fixing $\Phi$ over $\operatorname{dom}(\bar{L})$. We also define $\partial \mathcal{B}$ as the boundary of the domain $\bar{L}$ when $\bar{L}$ is considered as a function of $\dot{\mathcal{Q}}$ :

$$
\partial \mathcal{B}=\left\{\dot{\mathcal{Q}} \in \boldsymbol{B} \mid \text { there exists } \boldsymbol{i} \in \Omega_{I}, \boldsymbol{r} \in \Omega_{R^{k}}, k \in[K] \text { such that } \dot{\mathcal{Q}}_{\boldsymbol{i r}}^{k}=0\right\}
$$

# B. 3 Compactness of the level set 

The analysis of the EM algorithm often assumes the compactness of the level set to ensure that the accumulation points of any point sequence generated by the EM algorithm are included in the domain of the objective function. Please refer to the definition of the compact in Theorem 7. In this subsection, we prove that the level set is always compact in our proposed algorithm.
The level set is defined as follows:
Definition 2 (Level set). For a negative value $s<0$, we define the level set $F(s)$ as

$$
F(s)=\left\{\dot{\mathcal{Q}} \in \operatorname{dom}(L) \mid L(\dot{\mathcal{Q}}) \geq s\right\}
$$

To prove the compactness of the level set $F(s)$, we provide the following Proposition which shows that the level set is included in a compact set.
Proposition 4. Let $\boldsymbol{c}=\left(c_{\boldsymbol{i}}\right)_{\boldsymbol{i} \in \Omega_{I}^{o}}$ be real parameters where $c_{\boldsymbol{i}} \in(0,1)$ for any $\boldsymbol{i} \in \Omega_{I}^{o}$. We define a compact set in $\operatorname{dom}(L)$ as

$$
\mathcal{B}(\boldsymbol{c})=\left\{\dot{\mathcal{Q}} \in \mathcal{B} \mid \sum_{k} \sum_{\boldsymbol{r} \in \Omega_{R^{k}}} \dot{\mathcal{Q}}_{\boldsymbol{i r}} \geq c_{\boldsymbol{i}}\right\}
$$

Then, there exists a sufficiently small $\boldsymbol{c}$ such that $F(s) \subset \boldsymbol{B}(\boldsymbol{c})$ for any $s<0$.
Proof. For any $\dot{\mathcal{Q}} \in F(s)$, it holds that

$$
s \leq L(\dot{\mathcal{Q}}) \leq \mathcal{T}_{\boldsymbol{i}} \log \sum_{k} \sum_{\boldsymbol{r} \in \Omega_{R^{k}}} \dot{\mathcal{Q}}_{\boldsymbol{i r}}^{k}
$$

for any $\boldsymbol{i} \in \Omega_{I}$. Suppose $c_{\boldsymbol{i}} \leq \exp \left(s / \mathcal{T}_{\boldsymbol{i}}\right)$, then

$$
c_{\boldsymbol{i}} \leq \sum_{k} \sum_{\boldsymbol{r} \in \Omega_{R^{k}}} \dot{\mathcal{Q}}_{\boldsymbol{i r}}^{k}
$$

that means it holds that $\dot{\mathcal{Q}} \in \mathcal{B}(\boldsymbol{c})$ for any $\dot{\mathcal{Q}} \in F(s)$. Thus, we say $F(s) \subset \mathcal{B}(\boldsymbol{c})$.
Proposition 5. For any $s<0$, the level set $F(s)$ is compact.
Proof. Let $\left\{\dot{\mathcal{Q}}^{t}\right\}_{t \in \mathbb{N}}$ be any sequence of points in $F(s)$. From Proposition 4, the sequence $\left\{\dot{\mathcal{Q}}^{t}\right\}_{t \in \mathbb{N}}$ is included in a compact set $\boldsymbol{\mathcal { B }}(\boldsymbol{c})$. From Corollary 4 , the point sequence $\left\{\dot{\mathcal{Q}}^{t}\right\}_{t \in \mathbb{N}}$ has an accumulation point in $\mathcal{B}(\boldsymbol{c})$. Let $\left\{\dot{\mathcal{Q}}^{l_{m}}\right\}_{m \in \mathbb{N}}$ be a subsequence of $\left\{\dot{\mathcal{Q}}^{t}\right\}_{t \in \mathbb{N}}$ and $\dot{\mathcal{Q}}^{*}$ be its convergence point. Since the objective function $L$ is continuous in $\mathcal{B}(\boldsymbol{c}) \subset \operatorname{dom}(L)$, it holds that $L\left(\dot{\mathcal{Q}}^{*}\right) \geq s$, which means that the convergence point of any sequence of points in $F(s)$ is included in $F(s)$. Thus, from Corollary 4 , the level set $F(s)$ is compact.

The above result leads to the following propositions.
Corollary 2. $\check{\mathcal{Q}}^{*} \in \operatorname{dom}(L)$.
Proof. Since the objective function $L$ increases monotonically, it follows that $\check{\mathcal{Q}}^{t} \in F\left(L\left(\check{\mathcal{Q}}^{0}\right)\right)$ for any finite number $t \in \mathbb{N}$. Due to the compactness of the level set $F\left(L\left(\check{\mathcal{Q}}^{0}\right)\right)$, the limit point of the sequence in $F\left(L\left(\check{\mathcal{Q}}^{0}\right)\right)$ is in $F\left(L\left(\check{\mathcal{Q}}^{0}\right)\right)$. Furthermore, given the relationship $F\left(L\left(\check{\mathcal{Q}}^{0}\right)\right) \subset \operatorname{dom}(L)$, we conclude that $\check{\mathcal{Q}}^{*} \in \operatorname{dom}(L)$.
Corollary 3. $\left(\check{\mathcal{Q}}^{*}, \Phi^{*}\right) \in \operatorname{dom}(\bar{L})$.
Proof. Let $\left\{\left(\check{\mathcal{Q}}^{l_{m}}, \Phi^{l_{m}}\right)\right\}_{m \in \mathbb{N}}$ be a convergent subsequence of $\left\{\left(\check{\mathcal{Q}}^{t}, \Phi^{t}\right)\right\}_{t \in \mathbb{N}}$ and $\left(\check{\mathcal{Q}}^{*}, \Phi^{*}\right)$ be the convergence point of this subsequence. From Equation (10), the update rule for $\Phi$ in E-step is given as

$$
\Phi_{i r}^{k, l_{m}}=\frac{\check{\mathcal{Q}}_{i r}^{k, l_{m}}}{\sum_{k=1}^{K} \sum_{r \in \Omega_{R^{k}}} \check{\mathcal{Q}}_{i r}^{k, l_{m}}}
$$

Taking the limit $m \rightarrow \infty$, we obtain

$$
\Phi_{i r}^{k, *}=\frac{\check{\mathcal{Q}}_{i r}^{k, *}}{\sum_{k=1}^{K} \sum_{r \in \Omega_{R^{k}}} \check{\mathcal{Q}}_{i r}^{k, *}}
$$

Since Corollary 2 says $\sum_{k=1}^{K} \sum_{r \in \Omega_{R^{k}}} \check{\mathcal{Q}}_{i r}^{k, *} \geq c_{i}>0$ for any $i \in \Omega_{I}$, it follows that $\check{\mathcal{Q}}_{i r}^{k, *}=0 \Rightarrow$ $\Phi_{i r}^{k, *}=0$. Thus, $\left(\check{\mathcal{Q}}^{*}, \Phi^{*}\right) \in \operatorname{dom}(\bar{L})$.

# B. 4 Limit points on the stationary point or boundary of the domain 

For the accumulation point $\check{\mathcal{Q}}^{*}$ of the point sequence generated by the proposed method, we state that either the objective function $L\left(\check{\mathcal{Q}}^{*}\right)$ is a conditional stationary point, or $\check{\mathcal{Q}}^{*}$ is included in the boundary of the domain of $\bar{L}$, that is $\check{\mathcal{Q}}^{*} \in \partial \mathcal{B}$. As a formal statement, we provide the following theorem.
Theorem 5. Let $\left\{\check{\mathcal{Q}}^{t}\right\}_{t \in \mathbb{N}}$ be the sequence generated by the EM algorithm where $\check{\mathcal{Q}}^{t}=$ $\left(\check{\mathcal{Q}}^{1, t}, \ldots, \check{\mathcal{Q}}^{K, t}\right)$ and $\check{\mathcal{Q}}^{*}$ be the accumulation point of the sequence. If $\check{\mathcal{Q}}_{i r}^{k, *}>0$ for any $\boldsymbol{i} \in \Omega_{I}, \boldsymbol{r} \in \Omega_{R^{k}}, k \in[K]$, then $\check{\mathcal{Q}}^{*}$ is a conditional stationary point of the objective function $L$.
Proof. Let $\left\{\left(\check{\mathcal{Q}}^{t}, \Phi^{t}\right)\right\}_{t \in \mathbb{N}}$ be a sequence generated by the EM algorithm. By the BolzanoWeierstrass Theorem, every bounded sequence of real numbers has at least one convergent subsequence. Thus, let $\left\{\left(\check{\mathcal{Q}}^{l_{m}}, \Phi^{l_{m}}\right)\right\}_{m \in \mathbb{N}}$ be a convergent subsequence and $\check{\mathcal{Q}}^{*}, \Phi^{*}$ be the convergence point of this subsequence. By iterating the E and M steps on $\left(\check{\mathcal{Q}}^{l_{m}}, \Phi^{l_{m}}\right)$, we obtain the following inequality.

$$
\begin{aligned}
\bar{L}\left(\check{\mathcal{Q}}, \Phi^{l_{m}}\right) \leq & \bar{L}\left(\check{\mathcal{Q}}^{l_{m}+1}, \Phi^{l_{m}}\right) \\
\leq & \bar{L}\left(\check{\mathcal{Q}}^{l_{m}+1}, \Phi^{l_{m}+1}\right) \\
& \vdots \\
\leq & \bar{L}\left(\check{\mathcal{Q}}^{l_{m+1}}, \Phi^{l_{m+1}}\right)=L\left(\check{\mathcal{Q}}^{l_{m+1}}\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

where we used the monotonically increasing of lower bound in Equation (24) and the relation $l_{m}<l_{m}+1 \leq l_{m+1}$. The first inequality holds for any point $\check{\mathcal{Q}} \in \mathcal{B} \backslash \partial \mathcal{B}$ in the neighborhood of $\check{\mathcal{Q}}^{l_{m}}$ since each M-step finds optimal tensors $\check{\mathcal{Q}}$ in $\mathcal{B} \backslash \partial \mathcal{B}$. Due to Corollary 1 and the update rule in Equation (10), the objective function $L$ and its lower bound $\bar{L}$ do not fall into a discontinuous point. Then we can take the limit $m \rightarrow \infty$ to obtain the inequality

$$
\bar{L}\left(\check{\mathcal{Q}}, \Phi^{*}\right) \leq \bar{L}\left(\check{\mathcal{Q}}^{*}, \Phi^{*}\right)=L\left(\check{\mathcal{Q}}^{*}\right)
$$

which holds for any $\check{\mathcal{Q}} \in \mathcal{B} \backslash \partial \mathcal{B}$ in the neighborhood of $\check{\mathcal{Q}}^{*}$, which implies the point $\check{\mathcal{Q}}^{*}$ is the conditional stationary point of the lower bound $\bar{L}$. Thus, there exist real numbers $\lambda^{1, *}, \ldots, \lambda^{K, *}, \mu^{*}$

satisfying the following equations:

$$
\begin{aligned}
\frac{\partial}{\partial Z_{\boldsymbol{v}\left(h^{k}\right)}^{k, h^{k}}} \bar{L}\left(\check{\mathcal{Q}}^{*}, \Phi^{*}\right) & =\lambda^{k, *} \frac{\partial}{\partial Z_{\boldsymbol{v}^{k}\left(h^{k}\right)}^{k, h^{k}}} \prod_{h^{k}=1}^{H^{k}} Z_{\boldsymbol{v}^{k}\left(h^{k}\right)}^{k, h^{k}} \\
\frac{\partial}{\partial \eta^{k}} \bar{L}\left(\check{\mathcal{Q}}^{*}, \Phi^{*}\right) & =\mu^{*}
\end{aligned}
$$

where the left-hand sides are the partial derivative by factors of $\check{\mathcal{Q}}^{*}$. We note that it holds that $\left(\check{\mathcal{Q}}^{*}, \Phi^{*}\right) \in \operatorname{dom}(\bar{L})$ then, the lower bound $\bar{L}$ is partial differentiable with any factors of $\check{\mathcal{Q}}^{*}$ as discussed in Section B.2.2.
We define a function $G: \mathcal{B} \rightarrow \mathbb{R}$ as $G(\check{\mathcal{Q}})=L(\check{\mathcal{Q}})-\bar{L}\left(\check{\mathcal{Q}}, \Phi^{*}\right)$. As we see in Equation (28), the minimum value of the function $G(\check{\mathcal{Q}})$ is 0 at $\check{\mathcal{Q}}=\check{\mathcal{Q}}^{*}$. Thus, we obtain

$$
\begin{aligned}
\frac{\partial}{\partial Z_{\boldsymbol{v}\left(h^{k}\right)}^{k, h^{k}}} L\left(\check{\mathcal{Q}}^{*}\right)-\frac{\partial}{\partial Z_{\boldsymbol{v}\left(h^{k}\right)}^{k, h^{k}}} \bar{L}\left(\check{\mathcal{Q}}^{*}, \Phi^{*}\right) & =\lambda_{G}^{k} \frac{\partial}{\partial Z_{\boldsymbol{v}\left(h^{k}\right)}^{k, h^{k}}} \prod_{h^{k}=1}^{H^{k}} Z_{\boldsymbol{v}\left(h^{k}\right)}^{k, h^{k}} \\
\frac{\partial}{\partial \eta^{k}} L\left(\check{\mathcal{Q}}^{*}\right)-\frac{\partial}{\partial \eta^{k}} \bar{L}\left(\check{\mathcal{Q}}^{*}, \Phi^{*}\right) & =\mu_{G}
\end{aligned}
$$

Since it holds that $\check{\mathcal{Q}}^{*} \in \operatorname{dom}(L)$, the objective function $L$ is differentiable with any factors of $\check{\mathcal{Q}}^{*}$. Putting Equations (29) and (30) into the above equations, we obtain

$$
\begin{aligned}
\frac{\partial}{\partial Z_{\boldsymbol{v}\left(h^{k}\right)}^{k, h^{k}}} L\left(\check{\mathcal{Q}}^{*}\right) & =\left(\lambda^{k, *}+\lambda_{G}^{k}\right) \frac{\partial}{\partial Z_{\boldsymbol{v}\left(h^{k}\right)}^{k, h^{k}}} \prod_{h^{k}=1}^{H^{k}} Z_{\boldsymbol{v}^{k}\left(h^{k}\right)}^{k, h^{k}} \\
\frac{\partial}{\partial \eta^{k}} L\left(\check{\mathcal{Q}}^{*}\right) & =\mu^{*}+\mu_{G}
\end{aligned}
$$

which implies the objective function $L(\check{\mathcal{Q}})$ is conditional stationary point on $\mathcal{B}$ when $\check{\mathcal{Q}}=\check{\mathcal{Q}}^{*}$.
Since any bounded sequence of point converges to its set of accumulation points [52], the objective function of typical EM algorithm is guaranteed to converge to a stationary point under the assumptions of continuity for the cost function and its lower bound, as well as the compactness of the level set [27]. Although our proposed method satisfies all these assumptions as discussed so far, it should be noted that Theorem 5 does not demonstrate that every accumulation point is a stationary point of the objective function. Therefore, it is worth noting that even if all the elements in $\check{\mathcal{Q}}^{t}$ are positive for some sufficiently large $t$, it is not guaranteed that the proposed algorithm has converged to a set of stationary points since we cannot exclude the possibility of oscillation between the boundary of the domain and the set of stationary points.

# B. 5 Lemmata 

In this subsection, we summarize known results used in the above discussion.
Theorem 6 (The Bolzano-Weierstrass Theorem). Every bounded sequence in $\mathbb{R}^{N}$ has a convergent subsequence.

Theorem 7 (Heine-Borel Theorem). A subset in $\mathbb{R}^{N}$ is compact if and only if it is closed and bounded.

Corollary 4. A subset $S \subset \mathbb{R}^{N}$ is compact if and only if every sequence in $S$ has an accumulation point, and that accumulation point belongs to $S$.

Proof. It is evident from the Bolzano-Weierstrass Theorem, Heine-Borel Theorem, and the definition of closed sets in $\mathbb{R}^{N}$.

## C. 1 Technical detail for complicated low-rank structures

We decoupled the tensor many-body decomposition into independent problems in Section 4.3 using the basic property of logarithmic functions as:

$$
\begin{aligned}
& L_{\mathrm{MBA}}(\mathcal{M} ; \mathcal{Q}) \\
& =\sum_{i \in \Omega_{I}} \sum_{r \in \Omega_{R}} \mathcal{M}_{i r} \log \mathcal{G}_{r_{1} r_{2} r_{5}} A_{i_{1} r_{1}} B_{i_{2} r_{2}} C_{r_{5} r_{6}} D_{i_{3} r_{4}} \mathcal{H}_{r_{3} r_{6} r_{4}} E_{r_{4} i_{4}} \\
& =L_{\mathrm{MBA}}\left(\mathcal{M}^{\mathrm{Tucker}} ; \mathcal{Q}^{\mathrm{Tucker}}\right)+L_{\mathrm{MBA}}\left(\mathcal{M}^{\mathrm{TT}} ; \mathcal{Q}^{\mathrm{TT}}\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

We show here that the normalization for the model is satisfied when we use the solution formula of the many-body approximation for each decoupled problem.
In the following, we discuss the decomposition as described in Figure 4 as an example, while the generalization to arbitrary tree low-rank structures is straightforward. When we decouple the manybody approximation in Section 4.3 into the many-body approximation corresponding to the Tucker and Train decompositions, we need to guarantee that the normalizing condition

$$
\sum_{i \in \Omega_{I}} \sum_{r \in \Omega_{R}} \mathcal{Q}_{i r}=1
$$

is satisfied where we define

$$
\mathcal{Q}_{i r}=\mathcal{G}_{r_{1} r_{2} r_{5}} A_{i_{1} r_{1}} B_{i_{2} r_{2}} C_{r_{5} r_{6}} D_{i_{3} r_{3}} \mathcal{H}_{r_{3} r_{6} r_{4}} E_{r_{4} i_{4}}
$$

As explained at the beginning of Section A.1, we reduce scaling redundancy by scaling each factor and decouple the Lagrange function into independent parts. More specifically, we define a single root tensor and introduce normalized factors that sums over the edges that lie below from the root. Although the choice of the root tensor is not unique, we let tensor $\mathcal{G}$ be the root tensor and introduce

$$
\begin{array}{ll}
\tilde{A}_{i_{1} r_{1}}=\frac{1}{a_{r_{1}}} A_{i_{1} r_{1}}, & \tilde{B}_{i_{2} r_{2}}=\frac{1}{b_{r_{2}}} B_{i_{2} r_{2}}, \quad \tilde{C}_{r_{5} r_{6}}=\frac{h_{r_{6}}}{c_{r_{6}}} C_{r_{5} r_{6}} \\
\tilde{D}_{i_{3} r_{3}}=\frac{1}{d_{r_{3}}} D_{i_{3} r_{3}}, & \tilde{E}_{i_{4} r_{4}}=\frac{1}{e_{r_{4}}} E_{i_{4} r_{4}}, \quad \tilde{\mathcal{H}}_{r_{3} r_{4} r_{6}}=\frac{d_{r_{3}} e_{r_{4}}}{h_{r_{6}}} \mathcal{H}_{r_{3} r_{4} r_{6}}
\end{array}
$$

where each normalizer is defined as

$$
\begin{aligned}
a_{r_{1}} & =\sum_{i_{1}} A_{i_{1} r_{1}}, & b_{r_{2}}=\sum_{i_{2}} B_{i_{2} r_{2}}, & c_{r_{5}}=\sum_{r_{6}} C_{r_{5} r_{6}} h_{r_{6}} \\
d_{r_{3}} & =\sum_{i_{3}} D_{i_{3} r_{3}}, & e_{r_{4}}=\sum_{i_{4}} E_{i_{4} r_{4}}, & h_{r_{6}}=\sum_{r_{3} r_{4}} d_{r_{3}} e_{r_{4}} \mathcal{H}_{r_{3} r_{4} r_{6}}
\end{aligned}
$$

then it holds that

$$
\sum_{i_{1}} \tilde{A}_{i_{1} r_{1}}=\sum_{i_{2}} \tilde{B}_{i_{2} r_{2}}=\sum_{r_{6}} \tilde{C}_{r_{5} r_{6}}=\sum_{i_{3}} \tilde{D}_{i_{3} r_{3}}=\sum_{i_{4}} \tilde{E}_{i_{4} r_{4}}=\sum_{r_{3} r_{4}} \tilde{\mathcal{H}}_{r_{3} r_{4} r_{6}}=1
$$

We define the tensor $\tilde{\mathcal{G}}$ as $\tilde{\mathcal{G}}_{r_{1} r_{2} r_{5}}=a_{r_{1}} b_{r_{2}} c_{r_{5}} \mathcal{G}_{r_{1} r_{2} r_{5}}$ and putting Equations (33) and (34) into Equations (32) and (31), we obtain the normalizing condition for the root tensor $\mathcal{G}$ as

$$
\sum_{r_{1} r_{2} r_{5}} \tilde{\mathcal{G}}_{r_{1} r_{2} r_{5}}=1
$$

Then, the tensor $\mathcal{Q}$ can be written as

$$
\mathcal{Q}_{i r}=\tilde{\mathcal{G}}_{r_{1} r_{2} r_{5}} \tilde{A}_{i_{1} r_{1}} \tilde{B}_{i_{2} r_{2}} \tilde{C}_{r_{5} r_{6}} \tilde{D}_{i_{3} r_{3}} \tilde{\mathcal{H}}_{r_{3} r_{6} r_{4}} \tilde{E}_{r_{4} i_{4}}

# C. 3 Notation, terminology, and evaluation metric 

Although all symbols and technical terms are properly introduced in the main text, we provide our notation here for readability. The symbols $\mathbb{R}, \mathbb{R}_{\geq 0}$, and $\mathbb{N}$ denote the set of real, nonnegative real, and natural numbers, respectively. The set of all natural numbers less than or equal to a natural number $K$ is denoted by $[K]$. We use the Landau symbol $O$ for computational time complexity. The objective function of the EM algorithm is $L$, and its lower bound is written using overlined $L$ as $\bar{L}$.

Tensors We refer to a tensor whose elements all are nonnegative as a nonnegative tensor. The axes of a tensor are called its modes. The number of modes is called the order. For example, a vector is a first-order tensor, and a matrix is a second-order tensor. Tensors are denoted by calligraphic capital letters, as $\mathcal{T}, \mathcal{P}, \mathcal{Q}, \mathcal{M}$. A non-negative tensor whose sum over all indices is 1 is called a normalized tensor. Although the beginning and the last core tensors of the TT format are matrices rather than tensors, they are denoted by the calligraphic letters $\mathcal{G}^{(1)}$ and $\mathcal{G}^{(D)}$ for notational convenience. The element-wise product of a normalized non-negative tensor $\mathcal{Q}^{k}$ and a weight $\eta^{k}$ is written with a hat, e.g., $\mathcal{\mathcal { G }}^{k}=\eta^{k} \mathcal{Q}^{k}$. In the supplementary materials, tensors and matrices whose sums over some indices equal 1 are marked with a tilde as $\tilde{\mathcal{Q}}$.

Indices The visible variables $\boldsymbol{i}=\left(i_{1}, \ldots, i_{D}\right)$ and hidden variables $\boldsymbol{r}=\left(r_{1}, \ldots, r_{V}\right)$ are denoted as lower subscripts. The index set of visible variables and hidden variables are denoted as $\Omega_{I}$ and $\Omega_{R}$, respectively. Multiple tensors are represented using superscripts with parentheses, such as $\mathcal{G}^{(1)}, \ldots, \mathcal{G}^{(D)}$. Indices for mixtures are expressed as superscripts without parentheses. For example, the mixing ratio is represented by $\eta=\left(\eta^{1}, \ldots, \eta^{K}\right)$. The symbol $\Omega_{I}^{G}$ is for the set of indices of nonzero values of the tensor $\mathcal{T}$, that is, $\Omega_{I}^{G}=\left\{\boldsymbol{i} \mid \mathcal{T}_{\boldsymbol{i}} \neq 0\right\} \subseteq \Omega_{I}$.

Metric The proposed framework and baseline methods optimize the KL divergence between tensors [64], which is defined as

$$
D_{K L}(\mathcal{T}, \mathcal{P})=\sum_{\boldsymbol{i} \in \Omega_{I}}\left\{\mathcal{T}_{\boldsymbol{i}} \log \frac{\mathcal{T}_{\boldsymbol{i}}}{\mathcal{P}_{\boldsymbol{i}}}-\mathcal{T}_{\boldsymbol{i}}+\mathcal{P}_{\boldsymbol{i}}\right\}
$$

where $\mathcal{T}$ and $\mathcal{P}$ can be non-normalized or normalized tensors. For a given tensor $\mathcal{T}$, the optimization of the KL divergence for the tensor $\mathcal{P}$ is equivalent to the maximization of the cross-entropy or minimizing the negative log-likelihood per sample.

## C. 4 Limitations

The proposed framework only works on non-negative tensors. The theoretical analysis supporting the generalization performance of the mixture models remains in future work. While this study discussed low-rank structures with tree structures, such as CP, Tucker, and TT decomposition, and their combinations, we did not discuss tensor networks with loops. The method cannot be used directly in situations where there are missing values in the data. The method to decouple a complicated low-rank structure into solvable CP, Tucker, and TT decompositions is not unique. Thus, establishing an efficient decoupling method is also a subject for future work.

We download categorical tabular datasets Monk, SolarFlare, CarEvaluation, Nursery, SPECT, and Credit from the UCI database. ${ }^{1}$ Since there are missing values in Credit, we used only the features with no missing values in the experiment. We also download two categorical tabular datasets, GermanGSS and Parity5p5, from Penn Machine Learning Benchmarks [44]. Each dataset contains $N$ categorical samples $x_{n}=\left(i_{1}, \ldots, i_{D}\right)$ for $n=1, \ldots, N$. Both the number of samples, $N$, and the sample dimension, $D$, vary across datasets as seen in Table 2. In the original datasets, each $i_{d}$ represents a categorical quantity such as color, location, gender, etc. By mapping these to natural numbers, each feature $i_{d}$ is converted to a natural number from 1 to $I_{d}$, where $I_{d}$ is the degree of freedom in the $d$-th feature. We randomly select $70 \%$ of the $N$ samples to create the training index set $\Omega^{\text {train }}, 15 \%$ of samples to create the validation index set $\Omega^{\text {valid }}$, and the final $15 \%$ of the samples form the test index set $\Omega^{\text {test }}$. Some datasets may contain exactly the same samples. To deal with such datasets, we suppose that these indices sets may contain multiple identical elements.
We create empirical tensors $\mathcal{T}^{\text {train }}, \mathcal{T}^{\text {valid }}$, and $\mathcal{T}^{\text {test }}$, where each value $\mathcal{T}_{\boldsymbol{i}}^{\ell}$ is defined as the number of $i$ in the set $\Omega^{\ell}$ for $\ell \in\{$ train, valid, test $\}$. They are typically very sparse tensors. The above procedure to create empirical tensors is consistent with the discussion at the beginning of Section 4 We normalize each tensor by dividing all the elements by the sum of the tensor to map them to a discrete probability distribution.
During the training phase, by optimizing the log-likelihood

$$
D\left(\mathcal{T}^{\text {train }}, \mathcal{P}\right)=\sum_{\boldsymbol{i} \in \Omega^{\text {train }}} \mathcal{T}_{\boldsymbol{i}}^{\text {train }} \log \mathcal{P}_{\boldsymbol{i}}
$$

we decompose the tensor $\mathcal{T}^{\text {train }}$ to obtain the reconstructed tensor $\mathcal{P}$, which approximates $\mathcal{T}^{\text {train }}$. We adjust hyper-parameters such as tensor ranks, bounds, and learning rates to minimize the distance $D\left(\mathcal{T}^{\text {valid }}, \mathcal{P}\right)$. Finally, we evaluate the generalization error $D\left(\mathcal{T}^{\text {test }}, \mathcal{P}\right)$, where $\mathcal{P}$ is the reconstruction approximating $\mathcal{T}^{\text {train }}$ with tuned rank. Also, we conducted classification using obtained density $\mathcal{P}$. Specifically, the final feature $i_{D}$ in the density corresponds to the class label of the discrete item $\left(i_{1}, \ldots, i_{D-1}\right)$. Thus, for a given test sample $\left(j_{1}, \ldots, j_{D-1}\right)$, we see the estimated density $p\left(j_{1}, \ldots, j_{D-1}, c\right)$ for each class label $c$. The sample is then classified into the class $c$ that maximizes the density.
The proposed method and the baseline method have initial value dependence. Hence, all calculations were repeated five times to evaluate the mean and standard deviation of the negative log-likelihood per sample.

# E.1.2 Synthetic-data simulations 

We synthesize $8 \times 8 \times 8 \times 8 \times 8$ non-negative normalized tensors $\mathcal{U}^{\mathrm{CP}}$ and $\mathcal{U}^{\text {Train }}$ as follows:

$$
\mathcal{U}_{i_{1} i_{2} i_{3} i_{4} i_{5}}^{\mathrm{CP}}=\sum_{r} \mathcal{Q}_{i_{1} i_{2} i_{3} i_{4} r}^{\mathrm{CP}}, \quad \mathcal{U}_{i_{1} i_{2} i_{3} i_{4} i_{5}}^{\mathrm{Train}}=\sum_{r_{1} r_{2} r_{3}} \mathcal{Q}_{i_{1} i_{2} i_{3} i_{4} r_{1} r_{2} r_{3} r_{4}}^{\mathrm{Train}}
$$

Each element in the factors of the above tensors is independently sampled from a normal distribution, and its absolute value is taken. The tensor rank of $\mathcal{U}^{\mathrm{CP}}$ is 8 , and $\mathcal{U}^{\text {Train }}$ is $(4,4,4,4)$. We add a noise term with the weight $\eta^{\text {noise }}=0.10$ to these synthesized tensors and then normalize them. These tensors are regarded as true distributions. We obtain the samples from $\mathcal{U}^{\mathrm{CP}}$ and $\mathcal{U}^{\text {Train }}$ and randomly divide them into training and validation data.
We construct training tensors $\mathcal{T}$ from training data and factorize them using the proposed methods to obtain reconstructed low-rank tensors $\mathcal{P}^{k}$ for $k \in\{\mathrm{CP}$, Train, CPTrain $\}$. Next, we estimate the tensor ranks that best fit the validation data. Finally, we evaluate the KL divergence from the true distribution $\mathcal{U}^{k}$ to the reconstruction $\mathcal{P}^{k}$. This process is repeated with varying sample sizes.

## E.1.3 Datasets selection

We download the categorical tabular datasets from UCI and Penn Machine Learning Benchmarks. We here describe the Data Set Selection Criteria. Since sparsity is a natural assumption in the density estimation, completely dense data were excluded. Furthermore, as too many classes with too sparse data are not well suited for the considered classifications, whereas the complexity of the proposed approach is proportional to $N$, we chose datasets whose sparseness is larger than 1.0e-5 and $N<20000$ with fewer classes than 15 and with an empirical tensor of order larger than five.

## E. 2 Implementation detail

We describe the implementation details of the proposed and baseline methods in the following. All experiments are conducted by Python 3.12.3. We provide our source code for all experiments in the supplementary material.

## E.2.1 Proposed method

The pseudocodes for proposed methods are described in Algorithms 1 and 2. All tensors and mixture ratios were initialized with a uniform distribution between 0 and 1 and normalized as necessary. The algorithm was terminated when the number of iterations of the EM step exceeded 1200 or when the difference of the log-likelihood from the previous iteration was below 10e-8. For each low-rank model, the rank was gradually increased until the number of parameters in the model was half the number of samples.

## E.2.2 Baselines

BM and KLTrain We downloaded the source code for Positive Matrix Product State (KLTrain) and Real Born Machine (BM) from the official repository. ${ }^{2}$ The license of the code is described in the repository as MIT License. They optimize real-valued tensors and square each element to obtain nonnegative tensors. Each element of these real-valued tensors is initialized with the standard normal distribution. We varied the learning rates from $1.0 \mathrm{e}-4,1.0 \mathrm{e}-3, \ldots$ to 1.0 for training data. We then used the learning rate that yielded the smallest validation score. According to the description in the README file, the batch size was fixed at 20, and the number of iterations was set to 10,000. We performed each experiment five times with each bond and evaluated the mean and standard deviation. We varied the bond of the model as $1,2, \ldots, 8$, and evaluated the test data with the bond that best fits the validation data.

CNMFOPT We implemented CNMFOPT according to the original paper [26]. We iteratively optimize the factor matrices $A^{(1)}, \ldots, A^{(D)}$, and the weights $\lambda$ one after the other. We use the exponentiated gradient method [4] to optimize each factor matrix and weight. Although this optimization can be performed by closed-form update rules, all parameters cannot be updated simultaneously.

Thus, a loop is required for each update. This loop is called the inner iteration, which is repeated 100 times. The iterations of updating $\left(A^{(1)}, \ldots, A^{(D)}, \lambda\right)$ described above are called outer iteration. In the update rule for the exponential gradient method, the product of the derivative and the learning rate $\alpha$ is included in the exponential function. The learning rate $\alpha$ was selected from $0.005,0.001,0.0005$, 0.0001 , and 0.00005 to minimize the validation error. Learning with a larger learning rate was not feasible because it caused an overflow of the exponential function. The initial values of the parameters follow a uniform random distribution. The algorithm terminates when one of the following conditions is met: (1) We compute the KL divergence from the input data to the reconstruction after updating all factor matrices and weights. The change is less than 1.0e-4 compared to the previous outer loop. (2) The number of outer iterations exceeds 600 . When the condition (2) is met, the algorithm performs up to $60000(D+1)$ inner iterations in total.

# E. 3 Additional information for reproducibility 

Environment Experiments were conducted on Ubuntu 20.04.1 with a single core of 2.1 GHz Intel Xeon CPU Gold 5218 and 128GB of memory. This work does not require GPU computing. The total computation time for all experiments, including tuning the learning rate of the baselines, was less than 320 hours, using 88 threads of parallel computing.

Dataset detail, license, and availability We downloaded real-world datasets described in Table 2 through the Python package ucimlrepo and pmlb or GitHub repository ${ }^{2}$. UCI datasets, Solarflare, Monks, SPECT, Carevaluation, and Credit are licensed under a Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International (CC BY 4.0) license, as seen on each web page in the UCI database. ${ }^{1}$ The other two datasets, GermanGSS and Parity5p5, are licensed under MIT license as seen in the official GitHub repository ${ }^{3}$. The imported data were directly converted to tensors by the procedure described in Section E.1.

abstract:
We present an expectation-maximization (EM) based unified framework for
non-negative tensor decomposition that optimizes the Kullback-Leibler
divergence. To avoid iterations in each M-step and learning rate tuning, we
establish a general relationship between low-rank decompositions and many-body
approximations. Using this connection, we exploit that the closed-form solution
of the many-body approximation updates all parameters simultaneously in the
M-step. Our framework offers not only a unified methodology for a variety of
low-rank structures, including CP, Tucker, and Tensor Train decompositions, but
also their mixtures. Notably, the weights of each low-rank tensor in the
mixture can be learned from the data, which enables us to leverage the
advantage of different low-rank structures without careful selection of the
structure in advance. We empirically demonstrate that our framework overall
provides superior generalization in terms of discrete density estimation and
classification when compared to conventional tensor-based approaches.
